00:01:34.340 --> 00:01:38.110
It really means a lot to
me as an alum to be here.

00:01:38.110 --> 00:01:43.430
So in my work, I often start
with a basic phrase which

00:01:43.430 --> 00:01:46.060
is representations matter.

00:01:46.060 --> 00:01:48.510
And we've heard, and seen,
today how vitally important

00:01:48.510 --> 00:01:53.850
it is to have native peoples
and native voices in realms

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:56.800
from law to governance to
literature and art and, now,

00:01:56.800 --> 00:01:57.990
media.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:00.070
We live in a world
where the average person

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:04.300
spends 490 minutes a
day consuming media.

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:08.610
That is over eight hours,
over half of our waking day,

00:02:08.610 --> 00:02:13.220
and that's set to rise to
506 minutes by next year.

00:02:13.220 --> 00:02:15.170
And we know the type of
images that the public

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:16.807
is receiving of native peoples.

00:02:16.807 --> 00:02:18.390
I had a whole paragraph
going into it,

00:02:18.390 --> 00:02:21.740
but I think Matika did a
wonderful job talking about it.

00:02:21.740 --> 00:02:24.690
And these stereotypes
still dominate.

00:02:24.690 --> 00:02:26.840
These images, also, often
place native peoples

00:02:26.840 --> 00:02:28.670
in the historic past,
and we were never

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:30.670
pictured as contemporary
human beings,

00:02:30.670 --> 00:02:33.370
but always as something that
exists in stark contrast

00:02:33.370 --> 00:02:34.770
to modernity.

00:02:34.770 --> 00:02:38.020
The process of placing us in the
historic past, and therefore,

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:41.740
extinct, or as fantasy creatures
on the same level as mermaids

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:45.110
and wizards, obscures our
ongoing strengths, triumphs,

00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:47.150
and advances, but
it also obscures

00:02:47.150 --> 00:02:51.180
the real and pressing challenges
in our communities, as well.

00:02:51.180 --> 00:02:52.970
If native people
are only situated

00:02:52.970 --> 00:02:54.920
in the imaginations
of the public,

00:02:54.920 --> 00:02:57.010
we will never have the
support and understanding

00:02:57.010 --> 00:02:59.850
we need to move our
communities forward.

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:01.350
The other side of
misrepresentation,

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:03.650
for native peoples,
is invisibility.

00:03:03.650 --> 00:03:06.460
Because representations is
not just about stereotypes,

00:03:06.460 --> 00:03:08.840
it's also about the
lack of representations,

00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:11.530
or the all encompassing
invisibility native peoples

00:03:11.530 --> 00:03:13.980
experience in society.

00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:17.320
As an example, in an analysis
of prime time television shows

00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:21.850
between 1989-2009, researchers
found that native characters

00:03:21.850 --> 00:03:27.720
ranged between 0%-0.6%
of the overall numbers.

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:30.890
So in raw numbers, that
translates to only three

00:03:30.890 --> 00:03:32.370
native characters.

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:36.060
So three native characters in 20
years of prime time television

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:36.970
data.

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:38.760
And this invisibility
has real effects

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:40.620
on how native
peoples understand,

00:03:40.620 --> 00:03:42.210
in the words of
Stephanie Fryberg,

00:03:42.210 --> 00:03:44.870
and her colleague
Stephens, who they are

00:03:44.870 --> 00:03:47.500
and what they see as
possible for themselves.

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:50.050
Without counter narratives,
or positive representations,

00:03:50.050 --> 00:03:51.980
of native peoples to
draw upon, our ability

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:55.400
to imagine ourselves in
the future is limited.

00:03:55.400 --> 00:03:57.120
In this environment
of invisibility,

00:03:57.120 --> 00:04:00.740
every representation takes
on increased importance.

00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:03.500
On this panel, we have those who
have fought hard both within,

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:05.650
and outside of, the
film and media industry

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:08.340
to make change for native
peoples in these arenas,

00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:11.700
and to imagine what the future
of native film and media

00:04:11.700 --> 00:04:13.150
can look like.

00:04:13.150 --> 00:04:14.540
While so much of
the conversation

00:04:14.540 --> 00:04:17.019
is often about critique,
and while I believe

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:18.930
this is necessary
and very important--

00:04:18.930 --> 00:04:21.170
as it is what I do
every day on my blog--

00:04:21.170 --> 00:04:23.490
I am excited to be able to
share the stage with three

00:04:23.490 --> 00:04:25.930
native advocates who've
been making space

00:04:25.930 --> 00:04:28.550
for media by, and
for, native peoples,

00:04:28.550 --> 00:04:30.090
creating positive
counter narratives

00:04:30.090 --> 00:04:31.664
and disrupting stereotypes.

00:04:31.664 --> 00:04:33.830
What does it look like when
native peoples are given

00:04:33.830 --> 00:04:36.380
the power and control
to represent themselves

00:04:36.380 --> 00:04:38.190
in media and film?

00:04:38.190 --> 00:04:41.140
So on this panel we have Irene
Bedard, Migizi Pensoneau,

00:04:41.140 --> 00:04:42.950
and Loris Taylor.

00:04:42.950 --> 00:04:45.249
And I direct you to the
program to read their bios that

00:04:45.249 --> 00:04:47.290
demonstrate the depth and
breadth of knowledge we

00:04:47.290 --> 00:04:48.450
have on this stage.

00:04:48.450 --> 00:04:50.740
I'm really excited to
learn with you today.

00:04:50.740 --> 00:04:52.910
And without further
ado, I will turn it over

00:04:52.910 --> 00:04:54.189
to our first panelist, so

00:04:54.189 --> 00:04:54.980
[SPEAKING CHEROKEE]

00:04:54.980 --> 00:04:56.554
Thank you.

