00:05:04.298 --> 00:05:07.320
-[NON-ENGLISH] Thank you.

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:10.790
Thank you to the people
of this land, Wampanoag.

00:05:10.790 --> 00:05:18.050
Thank you, honorable colleagues,
honorable human beings,

00:05:18.050 --> 00:05:21.390
distinguished mothers and
fathers, daughters and sons,

00:05:21.390 --> 00:05:25.250
but especially our ancestors
and the coming generations.

00:05:25.250 --> 00:05:27.710
I am humbled and honored
to be in your presence

00:05:27.710 --> 00:05:32.430
at this critical juncture in
the arc of human existence.

00:05:32.430 --> 00:05:35.880
I'm Inupiaq, Yupik,
and Metis Cree.

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:38.110
My name Irene means peace.

00:05:38.110 --> 00:05:41.120
My Yupik name Kautaurak
means one who dropped.

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:42.950
[PTSEEW]

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:46.610
And my Cree name is Iron Woman
to the Core of the Earth.

00:05:49.210 --> 00:05:51.530
I was born and raised in Alaska.

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:53.960
And I'm the daughter of
Bruce and Carol Bedard

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:56.170
and the granddaughter of
David and Irene [? Oten ?]

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:58.260
from the village
of Kodiak, which

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:01.880
thrives from the gifts
of the Bering Sea.

00:06:01.880 --> 00:06:02.980
Yes.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:04.670
I am indigenous.

00:06:04.670 --> 00:06:09.100
But I am a citizen of the world,
a tiny human being on the face

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:13.090
the planet called Mother Earth.

00:06:13.090 --> 00:06:14.670
On this day before
you, I could speak

00:06:14.670 --> 00:06:16.170
of the villages
that have been moved

00:06:16.170 --> 00:06:18.670
inland due to the melting
of the Arctic Ocean,

00:06:18.670 --> 00:06:22.190
and the many more that the
Army Corps of Engineers

00:06:22.190 --> 00:06:24.580
plan to move in the near future.

00:06:24.580 --> 00:06:28.080
I could speak of the polar
bears or the cancer clusters

00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:31.120
attributed to the burning
of random found materials

00:06:31.120 --> 00:06:35.260
used to keep homes, in the long
winter, in the villages warm.

00:06:35.260 --> 00:06:38.500
But instead, as in the
tradition of my people,

00:06:38.500 --> 00:06:42.070
I am going to tell you a story.

00:06:42.070 --> 00:06:45.720
The story of us.

00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:50.410
I will begin with my
ancestor, my mother.

00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:53.070
She was born in the
village of Kodiak, Alaska

00:06:53.070 --> 00:06:56.310
in 1948, Cold War America.

00:06:56.310 --> 00:06:58.990
The United States government
was conducting tests

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:02.010
on the effects of nuclear
radiation on human beings,

00:07:02.010 --> 00:07:06.650
using the villagers of Point
Hope as their test subjects.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:11.000
But not so far away, in the
scheme of human history,

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:16.320
my mother was born and in her
lifetime lived 10,000 years.

00:07:16.320 --> 00:07:19.430
She lived the way we always
lived, subsistence hunting,

00:07:19.430 --> 00:07:21.170
fishing, and gathering.

00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:24.240
When she was still
a girl, an airplane

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:28.300
came, and took her to
the boarding school.

00:07:28.300 --> 00:07:30.620
From there she went to
the big city of Anchorage.

00:07:30.620 --> 00:07:34.180
And rode in a car,
though she never drove.

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:37.830
On television, she saw
a man land on the moon.

00:07:37.830 --> 00:07:40.700
Then came computers
and cell phones

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:45.730
and the world wide web
was cast around the world.

00:07:45.730 --> 00:07:48.560
She got to hear Elvis
sing on the radio,

00:07:48.560 --> 00:07:52.140
and then see him in a movie.

00:07:52.140 --> 00:07:55.340
You see, we human beings
have the same story.

00:07:55.340 --> 00:07:56.730
We all came from tribes.

00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:59.270
We all hail from the
Earth with songs,

00:07:59.270 --> 00:08:03.640
and stories, drums, and
dances, and the deep abiding

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:07.030
relationship to our ancestors,
the coming generations,

00:08:07.030 --> 00:08:08.980
and our Mother Earth.

00:08:08.980 --> 00:08:11.410
Our mother taught
us well how to live

00:08:11.410 --> 00:08:13.450
and from generation
to generation,

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:16.540
we pass the ancient
knowledge of our ecosystem,

00:08:16.540 --> 00:08:20.780
the plants, the animals, the
creatures of the sky and sea.

00:08:20.780 --> 00:08:23.640
We were one with
our environment.

00:08:23.640 --> 00:08:27.190
And she was our
blessed relation.

00:08:27.190 --> 00:08:29.870
But we human beings wanted
a sense of autonomy,

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:33.480
like any young person
leaving the nest.

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:37.830
Our intelligence, an integral
tool of our survival,

00:08:37.830 --> 00:08:39.370
became our wings.

00:08:39.370 --> 00:08:43.400
And we began our journey of
our eco-alienation, farming

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:46.310
and agriculture made way to
the Industrial Revolution.

00:08:46.310 --> 00:08:48.260
And only within
the last century,

00:08:48.260 --> 00:08:50.940
science became
our final answers.

00:08:50.940 --> 00:08:53.750
We cover our earth
with our compounds,

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:56.150
paving our way to the future.

00:08:56.150 --> 00:08:59.870
Separated lords over
our long history

00:08:59.870 --> 00:09:02.630
as children of an ecosystem.

00:09:02.630 --> 00:09:06.070
But now, on this
auspicious occasion,

00:09:06.070 --> 00:09:10.910
by the wisdom of humanity,
that science, our intelligence,

00:09:10.910 --> 00:09:13.330
is finding its way back.

00:09:13.330 --> 00:09:17.610
It is imperative to the survival
of the coming generations

00:09:17.610 --> 00:09:21.570
that we find ways to honor
and protect our relations,

00:09:21.570 --> 00:09:27.040
and bring us back to
balance with Mother Earth.

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:29.360
That was my speech
that I had prepared

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:31.990
for the United Nations.

00:09:31.990 --> 00:09:36.610
You see how a story
brings us all together.

00:09:36.610 --> 00:09:38.750
Healing through the
power of storytelling

00:09:38.750 --> 00:09:41.630
is what we do in
filmmaking and television.

00:09:41.630 --> 00:09:44.980
I only think of myself
as a storyteller.

00:09:44.980 --> 00:09:48.010
Yes, I'm just a
girl from Alaska,

00:09:48.010 --> 00:09:50.540
but I think I might be the
storyteller of my tribe.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:57.420
We have this report here
that I wanted to just show

00:09:57.420 --> 00:10:00.290
you, Inclusion or invisibility?

00:10:00.290 --> 00:10:04.660
Comprehensive Annenberg Report
on Diversity in Entertainment.

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:07.960
Let me just kind of push
through it really fast here.

00:10:07.960 --> 00:10:13.070
Gender, here we are speaking
of gender, and media platforms.

00:10:13.070 --> 00:10:14.865
Behind the camera
gender, as well.

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:18.840
We move forward.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:23.020
And here we have
race and ethnicity.

00:10:23.020 --> 00:10:25.090
You see the
prevalence onscreen--

00:10:25.090 --> 00:10:30.410
and thank you for bringing
up those numbers there.

00:10:30.410 --> 00:10:34.570
If you can see here,
forward, as we go forward,

00:10:34.570 --> 00:10:40.900
we have the film, broadcast
cable, streaming, and number

00:10:40.900 --> 00:10:44.910
of shows without any black
or Asian speaking characters

00:10:44.910 --> 00:10:47.800
by media platform.

00:10:47.800 --> 00:10:53.160
Betrayal on screen white,
Latino, black, Asian, other.

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:00.693
Other that what we get.

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:08.670
When I was growing up, I
wanted to be invisible.

00:11:08.670 --> 00:11:13.720
I was one of very few
native girls, native people,

00:11:13.720 --> 00:11:15.840
in the high school
that I went to.

00:11:15.840 --> 00:11:20.410
And it was so much
easier to be invisible.

00:11:20.410 --> 00:11:23.180
It was so much safer
to be invisible.

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:30.870
I read that book The Invisible
Man, and I understood.

00:11:30.870 --> 00:11:34.300
I felt a kinship to that.

00:11:34.300 --> 00:11:38.200
But we are the invisible people.

00:11:38.200 --> 00:11:43.930
Zero representation throughout
the last number of years,

00:11:43.930 --> 00:11:45.970
throughout most of those years.

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:51.170
Today, let's see, I'm on
a television series called

00:11:51.170 --> 00:11:54.510
Longmire, which was on A&amp;E
and got moved to a streaming

00:11:54.510 --> 00:11:55.614
network called Netflix.

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:05.650
But it's the story of
a really great guy who

00:12:05.650 --> 00:12:08.520
happens to be a cowboy Sheriff.

00:12:08.520 --> 00:12:15.530
We still continue to have these
conversations of invisibility,

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:19.310
these conversations
of our nature,

00:12:19.310 --> 00:12:23.820
of where we belong in the fabric
of-- not just American society,

00:12:23.820 --> 00:12:26.640
but the society
throughout this world.

00:12:26.640 --> 00:12:33.300
It's been a difficult
place to come from.

00:12:33.300 --> 00:12:36.130
But if you see, in this
picture, this is me.

00:12:36.130 --> 00:12:39.510
That parka was given
to be my grandmother.

00:12:39.510 --> 00:12:42.500
The fox was caught
by my grandfather.

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:46.130
That ring was
100-year-old Navajo ring.

00:12:46.130 --> 00:12:50.530
And I found out the turquoise in
it came all the way from Nepal.

00:12:50.530 --> 00:12:52.155
And it was given
to me by my father.

00:12:54.720 --> 00:12:55.833
We come to this place.

00:13:00.270 --> 00:13:01.820
Who controls the narrative?

00:13:01.820 --> 00:13:04.260
We go from building
bridges to the other

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:06.820
because that's what we're going
to have to do in this media

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:08.400
environment that we're in.

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:12.680
I was on a plane, while I was
filming a series called Into

00:13:12.680 --> 00:13:16.580
the West, which at
that time was a really

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:20.060
big deal in American Indian
country, especially those of us

00:13:20.060 --> 00:13:21.330
in front of the camera.

00:13:21.330 --> 00:13:25.380
There were 500 speaking
roles, and many of those roles

00:13:25.380 --> 00:13:28.810
were Native American people.

00:13:28.810 --> 00:13:32.900
This was an incredible story
that Steven Spielberg put

00:13:32.900 --> 00:13:36.170
forth, and incredibly
enough, he had

00:13:36.170 --> 00:13:40.300
to do the same thing
that the directors

00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:45.440
and producers of the film
Roots did 30 years before.

00:13:45.440 --> 00:13:47.790
He had to go in
and tell the story

00:13:47.790 --> 00:13:52.650
of a romance
between Lakota woman

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:54.930
and a Virginian
wheeler and their trek

00:13:54.930 --> 00:13:59.470
across-- during
westward expansion.

00:13:59.470 --> 00:14:02.290
That was how that story
needed to be pitched.

00:14:02.290 --> 00:14:07.880
It couldn't be pitched as a
story about the deconstruction

00:14:07.880 --> 00:14:10.660
of the American
Indian people, which

00:14:10.660 --> 00:14:12.015
is what it was really about.

00:14:17.010 --> 00:14:20.340
The reason I have this
picture up here right now.

00:14:20.340 --> 00:14:22.880
We all belong to the same bird.

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:27.400
It's important for us, all
of us, in this society,

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:31.570
to recognize that we are all
here, part of the same bird.

00:14:31.570 --> 00:14:36.490
We're all flying around the
universe on the same planet.

00:14:36.490 --> 00:14:40.970
And if we do not understand that
we are woven into the same rug,

00:14:40.970 --> 00:14:43.030
and allow each
thread to be who they

00:14:43.030 --> 00:14:46.020
are, to weave this
beautiful rug,

00:14:46.020 --> 00:14:50.570
then we are never going to
be whole under our feet.

00:14:50.570 --> 00:14:53.080
We are never going
to be able to fly,

00:14:53.080 --> 00:14:57.920
because we're not allowed
to be part of the same bird.

00:14:57.920 --> 00:15:00.940
And I was on this
plane, the Laker's jet,

00:15:00.940 --> 00:15:03.040
between Los Angeles
and New York when

00:15:03.040 --> 00:15:07.280
we were going to the big
junkets for Into the West.

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:09.560
And I'm sitting there
with the executives.

00:15:09.560 --> 00:15:13.390
And I'm talking to them
about some of the projects

00:15:13.390 --> 00:15:17.180
that I've thought of,
or that should be made,

00:15:17.180 --> 00:15:19.170
or that could be made.

00:15:19.170 --> 00:15:22.000
And he looked at me, and he
just basically, said, well,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:26.340
promoting in the middle of
promoting this major television

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:34.220
event, DreamWorks on
TNT, said, well you're

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:37.460
just not a demographic.

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:40.200
There are 400 million
indigenous people

00:15:40.200 --> 00:15:42.880
on this planet, let
alone the native people

00:15:42.880 --> 00:15:45.040
of this continent.

00:15:45.040 --> 00:15:49.010
Let alone people who have
an interest in who we are,

00:15:49.010 --> 00:15:51.300
and what we're about, and
the stories we have to tell,

00:15:51.300 --> 00:15:55.300
and what kinds of things we
have to offer to the planet,

00:15:55.300 --> 00:15:58.040
including our ancient
technologies, including

00:15:58.040 --> 00:16:02.390
the eyes and the ears and
voices of our grandmothers

00:16:02.390 --> 00:16:03.940
and our grandfathers.

00:16:03.940 --> 00:16:06.720
Including the next generation,
and the next generation,

00:16:06.720 --> 00:16:08.500
and the next
generation, things they

00:16:08.500 --> 00:16:13.030
should dream and see about
themselves on screen,

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:16.440
and know that they are part of
the fabric of the story telling

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:20.870
of us, all of us human beings.

00:16:20.870 --> 00:16:23.990
That's my mom and
her twin sister.

00:16:23.990 --> 00:16:25.492
Just had to put that in there.

00:16:25.492 --> 00:16:26.356
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:31.450 --> 00:16:33.180
My very first film
was a film called

00:16:33.180 --> 00:16:35.810
Squanto a Warrior's Tale.

00:16:35.810 --> 00:16:39.230
Squanto, you may
remember, was there

00:16:39.230 --> 00:16:41.470
at the first Thanksgiving.

00:16:41.470 --> 00:16:47.270
He was actually one of my
heroes before that because he

00:16:47.270 --> 00:16:51.500
was someone I knew from the
history books that represented

00:16:51.500 --> 00:16:55.690
who I am, or at least something
about what I understood

00:16:55.690 --> 00:16:59.750
in this world, the
people I came from,

00:16:59.750 --> 00:17:01.740
and that I was
represented in history.

00:17:01.740 --> 00:17:03.050
Woo hoo!

00:17:03.050 --> 00:17:05.069
That was so cool, right?

00:17:05.069 --> 00:17:08.859
And that we got this kind
of celebration once a year.

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:13.140
Well I call these characters
the Manifest Destiny characters.

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:16.180
I have, I feel very privileged,
to have had the chance to do

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:19.069
a lot of those characters.

00:17:19.069 --> 00:17:23.615
Squanto, in my understanding
of his story growing up,

00:17:23.615 --> 00:17:27.130
I was maybe told it a
little bit deeper than some.

00:17:27.130 --> 00:17:29.670
And then to be able
to be here on the set

00:17:29.670 --> 00:17:33.770
and to be able to tell this
story about this person who

00:17:33.770 --> 00:17:41.140
was plucked, kidnapped, sent
across this great big ocean,

00:17:41.140 --> 00:17:43.840
plucked, dropped in the
middle of civilization,

00:17:43.840 --> 00:17:48.470
shown off like an
animal, a creature.

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:51.300
He escaped and went
to a French monastery.

00:17:51.300 --> 00:17:55.610
Was there for decades
hoping to find passage home.

00:17:55.610 --> 00:17:57.070
Finally, found passage home.

00:17:57.070 --> 00:18:00.390
And when he got there
his entire people

00:18:00.390 --> 00:18:04.600
were gone from
warfare and disease.

00:18:04.600 --> 00:18:06.930
So he found his way
to another village.

00:18:06.930 --> 00:18:10.560
And he could have very easily,
when those pilgrims came,

00:18:10.560 --> 00:18:13.280
said Ah, sorry.

00:18:13.280 --> 00:18:15.750
You just go ahead and starve.

00:18:15.750 --> 00:18:17.890
But he didn't.

00:18:17.890 --> 00:18:19.930
He saw that they
were human beings.

00:18:19.930 --> 00:18:23.230
And he had empathy
and compassion.

00:18:23.230 --> 00:18:27.010
And he did what he
did, yes, and that

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:30.260
is why he ended out
in our history books.

00:18:30.260 --> 00:18:34.490
But at the same time,
would you have done that?

00:18:34.490 --> 00:18:36.680
Would you have?

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:39.800
To me that is so
telling of the love that

00:18:39.800 --> 00:18:43.950
was spoken of earlier, of
the love and the compassion

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:49.400
that we have for one another
as a tribe, as a people.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:54.420
My grandfather said Bunning,
what does Inupiaq mean?

00:18:54.420 --> 00:18:56.650
And I said, I don't know.

00:18:56.650 --> 00:18:59.069
He said it just
means human being.

00:18:59.069 --> 00:19:01.610
When you go out into the world--
when I left to go to college

00:19:01.610 --> 00:19:04.590
and I was going all the way to
the other side of the planet,

00:19:04.590 --> 00:19:06.890
as far as I knew-- I dropped in.

00:19:06.890 --> 00:19:09.200
It was 90 degrees
and 90% humidity

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:11.020
and I had no idea what that was.

00:19:11.020 --> 00:19:13.990
But his words kept me.

00:19:13.990 --> 00:19:16.780
You just look people in
the eyes and you will see

00:19:16.780 --> 00:19:19.510
that they are a human being.

00:19:19.510 --> 00:19:22.990
It's all about the story.

00:19:22.990 --> 00:19:26.300
I look you in the eyes and
I want to know your story.

00:19:28.830 --> 00:19:31.304
There is a lot of healing in
the power of storytelling.

00:19:34.410 --> 00:19:37.230
Later on, actually my
second film that I did

00:19:37.230 --> 00:19:40.970
was a film called Lakota
Woman Siege at Wounded Knee.

00:19:40.970 --> 00:19:45.060
It was about the siege at
Wounded Knee in 199-- 1993--

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:50.290
1973, we actually
filmed in 1993.

00:19:50.290 --> 00:19:56.860
And I had the chance to portray
Mary Crow Dog, Lakota woman.

00:19:56.860 --> 00:19:59.970
I had the chance to be
there with the people, many

00:19:59.970 --> 00:20:03.680
of the people who
were there in 1973.

00:20:03.680 --> 00:20:09.440
I had a chance to
go to Wounded Knee.

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:15.720
I had a chance to see, and
hear, and listen to the voices.

00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:19.280
I listened to the voice of Mary.

00:20:19.280 --> 00:20:22.800
And I had read the book
before, when I was in college.

00:20:22.800 --> 00:20:27.020
I had sent that book to my mom,
and my sister, and my aunties,

00:20:27.020 --> 00:20:28.660
because I understood.

00:20:28.660 --> 00:20:30.180
I knew this story.

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:34.250
And when I actually met
her, I had heard her voice,

00:20:34.250 --> 00:20:38.500
before I had ever even really
actually physically heard her.

00:20:38.500 --> 00:20:42.340
That's the connection
that media has.

00:20:42.340 --> 00:20:45.060
We connect ourselves
to each other.

00:20:47.930 --> 00:20:50.410
In physics, you know,
there's entanglement.

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:53.120
Well, that's what
storytelling is.

00:20:53.120 --> 00:20:54.760
It's our entanglement.

00:20:54.760 --> 00:20:58.550
And it shows that we are not
so different from each other,

00:20:58.550 --> 00:21:02.950
but it also shows that
another point of view.

00:21:02.950 --> 00:21:05.020
It gives us a chance
to see through the eyes

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:08.350
and walk through the
feet of someone else.

00:21:08.350 --> 00:21:10.950
Someone that we maybe
never got the chance

00:21:10.950 --> 00:21:15.200
to meet or understand.

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:18.846
It creates a bridge of
compassion and empathy.

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:25.770
I show this one.

00:21:25.770 --> 00:21:30.630
This was a film where I got
to play a tough tribal cop.

00:21:30.630 --> 00:21:32.460
Right?

00:21:32.460 --> 00:21:39.000
When I open up my little
phone here and I, see inbox.

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:43.200
Oh, I have a meeting, or
a script has been sent,

00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:45.600
I know that I'm
going to be looking

00:21:45.600 --> 00:21:49.320
at a handful of characters.

00:21:49.320 --> 00:21:57.890
Is it going to be the angry,
tough political hates-all

00:21:57.890 --> 00:22:02.400
[NON-ENGLISH] woman?

00:22:02.400 --> 00:22:05.300
Is it going to be the
disenfranchised, poverty

00:22:05.300 --> 00:22:09.830
stricken mother,
you know, victim?

00:22:09.830 --> 00:22:13.580
Victim of something,
whether it's rape,

00:22:13.580 --> 00:22:17.415
or-- I've been killed
in so many ways.

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:21.780
It's true.

00:22:21.780 --> 00:22:27.890
I actually spent one on
two different locations,

00:22:27.890 --> 00:22:32.090
on opposite sides of country,
set in two different centuries.

00:22:32.090 --> 00:22:34.440
And in that same week,
I spent two whole days

00:22:34.440 --> 00:22:35.980
hanging in two different trees.

00:22:39.580 --> 00:22:46.520
Let's see, the wise
sage, medicine person

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:53.950
who lacks any sense of
humor or humanity, really.

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:58.570
The alcoholic, drug
addicted crazy.

00:22:58.570 --> 00:23:00.140
That's it.

00:23:00.140 --> 00:23:03.490
That's what I think of when I'm
about ready to open a script,

00:23:03.490 --> 00:23:06.340
which one is it?

00:23:06.340 --> 00:23:12.490
I just know if you go out and
with Sleeping Lady Films Waking

00:23:12.490 --> 00:23:15.800
Giants Productions, we
have too many stories.

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:18.640
And good news from
Indian country.

00:23:18.640 --> 00:23:21.370
Good news from the
indigenous world.

00:23:21.370 --> 00:23:24.110
There are so many
positive, amazing stories

00:23:24.110 --> 00:23:27.350
of perseverance, and
strength, and dignity.

00:23:27.350 --> 00:23:29.540
And even the stories that
are hard and difficult

00:23:29.540 --> 00:23:33.190
and should be told because
these are the stories that so

00:23:33.190 --> 00:23:36.060
many people just
don't even know,

00:23:36.060 --> 00:23:40.280
we tell them with inspiration.

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:47.780
We tell them with a heart of
all human kind, of all mothers,

00:23:47.780 --> 00:23:53.430
of all grandmothers, and their
grandmothers before them,

00:23:53.430 --> 00:23:57.370
and the child, and the
daughter, and the daughters down

00:23:57.370 --> 00:24:00.950
seven generations from me.

00:24:00.950 --> 00:24:06.910
That connection that I
have with the projects

00:24:06.910 --> 00:24:11.170
that I do, and I've had to
be a part of they're amazing.

00:24:11.170 --> 00:24:13.130
I'm so blessed and honored.

00:24:16.690 --> 00:24:19.450
I walk in beauty.

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:22.620
I think it's-- I show these
pictures because this goes

00:24:22.620 --> 00:24:25.930
back, this is the flapper era,
little bit before the flapper

00:24:25.930 --> 00:24:26.630
era.

00:24:26.630 --> 00:24:28.150
And doesn't she look native?

00:24:28.150 --> 00:24:29.050
She's not.

00:24:29.050 --> 00:24:33.650
But that depiction, the
kind of understanding,

00:24:33.650 --> 00:24:35.860
of we as native
women and the beauty

00:24:35.860 --> 00:24:43.710
that we hold, inherently,
it is a wanted--

00:24:43.710 --> 00:24:45.360
there is something about it.

00:24:45.360 --> 00:24:49.210
There is something about the
beauty of a native woman.

00:24:49.210 --> 00:24:52.200
And about the fact that
we do walk in beauty

00:24:52.200 --> 00:24:55.550
to the best of our abilities, in
the hardest and most difficult

00:24:55.550 --> 00:24:57.550
circumstances.

00:24:57.550 --> 00:24:58.660
We continue to do so.

00:25:02.720 --> 00:25:10.540
Even if Barbie would look
like this, if she was really

00:25:10.540 --> 00:25:11.907
a human-sized person.

00:25:14.650 --> 00:25:18.130
This was something that
very much came up--

00:25:18.130 --> 00:25:20.610
and I'm trying to find
where that one is, actually.

00:25:20.610 --> 00:25:27.970
I think it's out of
sequence-- with the avatar,

00:25:27.970 --> 00:25:30.514
with Pocahontas, which
of course, a lot of you

00:25:30.514 --> 00:25:32.180
know that I was the
voice of Pocahontas.

00:25:32.180 --> 00:25:34.710
And then I went on and did The
New World by Terrence Malick,

00:25:34.710 --> 00:25:36.800
and I played
Pocahontas's mother.

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:39.335
Keep on going on, don't we.

00:25:43.660 --> 00:25:46.900
There's that
sexualization, also,

00:25:46.900 --> 00:25:51.750
that has happened to Native
American and indigenous women.

00:25:51.750 --> 00:25:56.340
And of course, that
includes sexual violence.

00:25:56.340 --> 00:26:00.520
John Smith, actually,
no matter where he went,

00:26:00.520 --> 00:26:08.900
he had these grand, amazing
adventures, and generally

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:15.180
some beautiful, indigenous,
wild thing did something grand

00:26:15.180 --> 00:26:16.740
and amazing in his life.

00:26:16.740 --> 00:26:22.010
And with Pocahontas,
though, the one thing

00:26:22.010 --> 00:26:27.790
that really struck me
about the story in itself,

00:26:27.790 --> 00:26:30.800
was she threw herself
upon John Smith

00:26:30.800 --> 00:26:32.950
when she was only 11 years old.

00:26:32.950 --> 00:26:36.820
And she stopped a
war from happening.

00:26:36.820 --> 00:26:42.030
And so that's why we talk about
the peace of Pocahontas, right?

00:26:42.030 --> 00:26:47.710
But I think that inherent story
within itself, whether it's

00:26:47.710 --> 00:26:53.110
true or not, that story
that we cling to about it

00:26:53.110 --> 00:26:58.800
is the story that-- I
think the reason we cling

00:26:58.800 --> 00:27:02.010
to these stories is
that it is something

00:27:02.010 --> 00:27:04.090
that we hope and wish for.

00:27:04.090 --> 00:27:07.680
We want the happy endings.

00:27:07.680 --> 00:27:10.990
We want that sense of dignity.

00:27:10.990 --> 00:27:12.100
And you know what?

00:27:12.100 --> 00:27:14.110
As far as Disney
princesses go, she

00:27:14.110 --> 00:27:17.190
wasn't waiting for her
prince to come and save her.

00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:19.170
She saved him.

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:20.210
So moving on.

00:27:25.080 --> 00:27:26.945
My time is up.

00:27:26.945 --> 00:27:28.946
Winona LaDuke, strong woman.

