And if one of you people
comes up after this

00:30:51.890 --> 00:30:54.840
and asks me where we got that
name-- just figure it out.

00:30:58.630 --> 00:31:03.090
So we started off
with-- there are

00:31:03.090 --> 00:31:05.130
five of us in the group,
myself, Sterlin Harjo's

00:31:05.130 --> 00:31:07.540
the filmmaker, Bobby Wilson,
you guys might know him

00:31:07.540 --> 00:31:10.680
with the tattoos
on his neck, Dallas

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:13.460
Goldtooth, my little
brother, and Ryan Red Corn,

00:31:13.460 --> 00:31:16.500
who we affectionately call
the white guy, because he's

00:31:16.500 --> 00:31:19.490
very pale.

00:31:19.490 --> 00:31:21.740
But we are all artists
in different rights.

00:31:21.740 --> 00:31:22.760
So I'm a screenwriter.

00:31:22.760 --> 00:31:24.468
Sterlin Harjo, as I
said, is a filmmaker.

00:31:24.468 --> 00:31:26.700
Bobby Wilson is a
fantastic artist.

00:31:26.700 --> 00:31:28.230
Ryan Red Corn is a
graphic designer.

00:31:28.230 --> 00:31:30.940
And my little brother, Dallas,
is like this powerhouse

00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:32.740
of activism in any country.

00:31:32.740 --> 00:31:39.860
And so why do we get together
and put these videos online,

00:31:39.860 --> 00:31:42.050
like which are really,
really self-deprecating?

00:31:42.050 --> 00:31:44.460
I mean if you have
any desire, and you

00:31:44.460 --> 00:31:48.370
shouldn't, to see what I
look like under this, you

00:31:48.370 --> 00:31:49.470
could find it online.

00:31:55.620 --> 00:31:56.580
I'm just saying.

00:31:56.580 --> 00:31:58.570
All right.

00:31:58.570 --> 00:32:03.230
So but we put up a
video and, again,

00:32:03.230 --> 00:32:06.180
I'm sorry I don't have anything
for you-- I mean that would

00:32:06.180 --> 00:32:07.750
take up all of my
time-- our videos

00:32:07.750 --> 00:32:11.207
generally they range from
2-10 minutes in length.

00:32:11.207 --> 00:32:13.790
If I were to show a few, then
it would just eat up everything.

00:32:13.790 --> 00:32:16.380
But you can look us up,
1491s, YouTube, Facebook,

00:32:16.380 --> 00:32:18.350
all that stuff.

00:32:18.350 --> 00:32:20.800
But we put a video up.

00:32:20.800 --> 00:32:22.730
And we didn't think
anything of it.

00:32:22.730 --> 00:32:23.650
We were, like oh,
yeah, this is just

00:32:23.650 --> 00:32:24.900
for friends, family, whatever.

00:32:24.900 --> 00:32:27.600
Laugh at us, laugh at ourselves.

00:32:27.600 --> 00:32:32.790
But the next week, we're at
tens of thousands of views.

00:32:32.790 --> 00:32:34.830
And this is at the
advent of YouTube.

00:32:34.830 --> 00:32:36.950
It was just sort of
starting as a platform.

00:32:36.950 --> 00:32:40.090
And we're like oh,
there's something here.

00:32:40.090 --> 00:32:43.580
And like good Indian men, we
didn't do anything for a couple

00:32:43.580 --> 00:32:47.400
years, we sat on it.

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:50.050
But we just let you down.

00:32:53.010 --> 00:32:55.932
So we ended up, finally,
after a year or two,

00:32:55.932 --> 00:32:57.140
we finally got back together.

00:32:57.140 --> 00:32:58.000
And we're like, man,
let's do this again.

00:32:58.000 --> 00:32:59.190
And we made a bunch more videos.

00:32:59.190 --> 00:33:00.550
And they became just as popular.

00:33:00.550 --> 00:33:04.190
And we're like, oh, this isn't
just a fluke, one time thing.

00:33:04.190 --> 00:33:06.900
People like seeing us
joke about ourselves.

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:09.600
And let's continue.

00:33:09.600 --> 00:33:13.650
And as we continued, we noticed
that the more places that we

00:33:13.650 --> 00:33:17.130
got to go and get brought, and
the more places, we performed,

00:33:17.130 --> 00:33:20.280
we noticed that
outside of us, there

00:33:20.280 --> 00:33:25.700
was this sort of dearth,
this void of native humor.

00:33:25.700 --> 00:33:27.140
Which is funny
because you always

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:30.880
hear native people talking
about our humor is our medicine,

00:33:30.880 --> 00:33:32.740
our humor is what
keeps us strong.

00:33:32.740 --> 00:33:36.560
And I'm like show
it to me in a movie.

00:33:36.560 --> 00:33:40.220
I mean outside of like
Smoke Signals or something

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:45.960
like that where, but even
that humor is it sort of a let

00:33:45.960 --> 00:33:48.850
me explain this to the general
audience kind of humor as well.

00:33:48.850 --> 00:33:51.430
There are humorous bits in it
that are for native people,

00:33:51.430 --> 00:33:54.480
and stuff, but a lot of it is
like that scene where they're

00:33:54.480 --> 00:33:57.390
going backwards in the car-- the
two women are going backwards

00:33:57.390 --> 00:33:59.000
in the car.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:03.390
That is a scene
that I really liked

00:34:03.390 --> 00:34:05.889
and then I really
hated right afterwards.

00:34:05.889 --> 00:34:07.430
Because it was like,
oh that's great,

00:34:07.430 --> 00:34:08.584
just a quirky little thing.

00:34:08.584 --> 00:34:10.500
It's funny they're driving
this car backwards.

00:34:10.500 --> 00:34:11.330
It's awesome.

00:34:11.330 --> 00:34:12.913
But then it got into
this conversation

00:34:12.913 --> 00:34:14.880
about oh, you're going
to need your passports.

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:16.860
And you're like OK.

00:34:16.860 --> 00:34:21.360
So let's explain that
natives are an other.

00:34:21.360 --> 00:34:23.570
We really seriously don't
need to explain that.

00:34:23.570 --> 00:34:25.330
Natives have been
portrayed as an other

00:34:25.330 --> 00:34:30.070
for generations and
generations, since the founding.

00:34:30.070 --> 00:34:35.837
And so when I saw that
as a young guy, when

00:34:35.837 --> 00:34:37.670
Smoke Signals came out,
I was like holy shit

00:34:37.670 --> 00:34:39.440
this is entirely like
me to produce thing.

00:34:39.440 --> 00:34:40.080
It's huge.

00:34:40.080 --> 00:34:41.270
It's amazing.

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:42.960
What's the next
thing going to be?

00:34:42.960 --> 00:34:45.520
And there were a lot of things
that were under the radar.

00:34:45.520 --> 00:34:49.570
You know Smoke
Signals was so big.

00:34:49.570 --> 00:34:51.429
And so the other thing
I started to notice

00:34:51.429 --> 00:34:54.310
when we were doing
our 1491s and the more

00:34:54.310 --> 00:34:58.680
that we produced-- and we have
over 100 now-- not all of them

00:34:58.680 --> 00:34:59.180
are funny.

00:34:59.180 --> 00:35:01.380
Some of them are from a
series we call Represent where

00:35:01.380 --> 00:35:02.950
we go to different
places and we're like,

00:35:02.950 --> 00:35:04.408
here you take the
cameras and we'll

00:35:04.408 --> 00:35:08.920
put them on our channel,
that kind of thing.

00:35:08.920 --> 00:35:12.250
But the more we did that,
the more that I personally

00:35:12.250 --> 00:35:18.170
started to notice that
it's not just like humor,

00:35:18.170 --> 00:35:23.560
we're not telling a lot
of different stories here.

00:35:23.560 --> 00:35:26.220
So if I were to tell
you-- and it's funny,

00:35:26.220 --> 00:35:28.180
because Irene is in
Smoke Signals and so

00:35:28.180 --> 00:35:29.554
I did this to her earlier.

00:35:29.554 --> 00:35:31.720
I was all hey, I'm going
to describe a movie to you.

00:35:31.720 --> 00:35:33.760
Young man, through some
tragic happenstance,

00:35:33.760 --> 00:35:35.260
has to go on a
journey, young angry,

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:37.030
native man has to
go on a journey

00:35:37.030 --> 00:35:40.000
and come to terms with himself
and his own Indianness,

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:41.740
his identity, what
movie is that?

00:35:41.740 --> 00:35:43.227
What movie am I describing?

00:35:43.227 --> 00:35:44.810
And so because I
just talked about it,

00:35:44.810 --> 00:35:46.680
you could go like oh
that's Smoke Signals.

00:35:46.680 --> 00:35:48.320
Oh, wait, no, that's
Powwow Highway.

00:35:48.320 --> 00:35:50.130
Oh, wait, no, it's Four
Sheets to the Wind.

00:35:50.130 --> 00:35:51.463
Oh, no, it's Drunktown's Finest.

00:35:53.644 --> 00:35:54.810
There are different aspects.

00:35:54.810 --> 00:35:57.830
And I'm like, where all
of these are coming from?

00:35:57.830 --> 00:36:01.410
And part of it is that native
people have not had a chance

00:36:01.410 --> 00:36:02.660
to tell their stories yet.

00:36:02.660 --> 00:36:05.330
And so I feel like
native people definitely

00:36:05.330 --> 00:36:07.899
want to throw in a
lot of explanation.

00:36:07.899 --> 00:36:09.440
Like this is where
we come from, this

00:36:09.440 --> 00:36:11.560
is what you missed, see
all this that you missed?

00:36:11.560 --> 00:36:16.810
But the story-- it gets in
the way of the story moving.

00:36:16.810 --> 00:36:20.497
And so I was thinking
to myself like man,

00:36:20.497 --> 00:36:21.580
where does that come from?

00:36:21.580 --> 00:36:24.390
Why is that so ingrained?

00:36:24.390 --> 00:36:26.000
And who are these characters?

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:30.473
As Irene was talking
about, there are a few

00:36:30.473 --> 00:36:35.270
that native women can
play, and they're not nice.

00:36:35.270 --> 00:36:37.500
My Auntie Casey Camp
is also an actor.

00:36:37.500 --> 00:36:41.320
And she want to do a
1491s video one day that

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:44.574
is her doing like an acting
camp for native women

00:36:44.574 --> 00:36:45.990
where she's just
like, this is how

00:36:45.990 --> 00:36:50.174
you lay next to the tipi
that's on fire, dead.

00:36:50.174 --> 00:36:51.590
And she's really
excited about it.

00:36:51.590 --> 00:36:52.631
We want to do it someday.

00:36:52.631 --> 00:36:55.148
So it's really messed up.

00:36:58.084 --> 00:37:00.000
But we're like, OK, where
does that come from?

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:03.090
And so I started thinking
and then I figured it out.

00:37:03.090 --> 00:37:06.250
The words were written up
there during Irene's thing,

00:37:06.250 --> 00:37:11.000
and it's a loaded thing.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:12.400
We could talk forever about it.

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:16.470
But it's this idea of
Manifest Destiny right?

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:18.460
God put this thing
here, put this land here

00:37:18.460 --> 00:37:23.760
for it to be
conquered, taking over,

00:37:23.760 --> 00:37:26.820
for good European
Americans to come in

00:37:26.820 --> 00:37:31.490
and cultivate the wilderness,
make something out of it,

00:37:31.490 --> 00:37:33.250
make something out of yourself.

00:37:33.250 --> 00:37:37.127
And that ideal is one of
the more detrimental things

00:37:37.127 --> 00:37:38.960
that happened to native
people, particularly

00:37:38.960 --> 00:37:41.290
in terms of imagery.

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:45.000
When you think about
the images that

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:48.250
have come out of just
that one concept, things

00:37:48.250 --> 00:37:56.430
like the end of the trail, oh,
I'm on my horse and I'm tired.

00:37:56.430 --> 00:37:57.700
I'm defeated.

00:37:57.700 --> 00:38:01.090
Or you think about like
the Indian maiden thing,

00:38:01.090 --> 00:38:05.210
this native woman that's there
for the white man to conquer.

00:38:05.210 --> 00:38:09.330
And you think about that.

00:38:09.330 --> 00:38:12.820
And you think about the
idea that native people,

00:38:12.820 --> 00:38:16.130
for a long time represented,
the wilderness of America,

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:19.020
the wild, the beast, the savage.

00:38:19.020 --> 00:38:22.230
And that is meant to be
tamed, meant to be conquered.

00:38:22.230 --> 00:38:23.710
What does that mean for a man?

00:38:23.710 --> 00:38:25.130
It means you need to be beaten.

00:38:25.130 --> 00:38:27.588
You know American lives on this
idea that natives are dead.

00:38:28.220 --> 00:38:30.680
When you fuck with
that idea, it's

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:32.670
problematic for a lot of people.

00:38:32.670 --> 00:38:33.820
When you go, no, no, no.

00:38:33.820 --> 00:38:33.910
I'm alive.

00:38:33.910 --> 00:38:34.493
I got a voice.

00:38:34.493 --> 00:38:36.210
I'm going to say some shit.

00:38:36.210 --> 00:38:38.110
You're like, [GIBBERISH].

00:38:38.110 --> 00:38:39.536
Then, what is America?

00:38:42.194 --> 00:38:43.360
Saw a couple of you in here.

00:38:43.360 --> 00:38:44.735
I'm like, no, I'm
talking to you.

00:38:44.735 --> 00:38:45.580
I'm swearing at you.

00:38:45.580 --> 00:38:47.062
My god.

00:38:47.062 --> 00:38:49.650
Just trying to duck arrows
and tomahawks and whatnot.

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:54.900
Of words.

00:38:54.900 --> 00:38:57.150
Verbal tomahawks is what
I'm launching in your faces.

00:39:01.980 --> 00:39:03.570
Yeah, I just said that.

00:39:03.570 --> 00:39:05.940
All right.

00:39:05.940 --> 00:39:06.492
But no, man.

00:39:06.492 --> 00:39:07.950
Like when you mess
with that idea--

00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:10.460
and America, when
you think about it,

00:39:10.460 --> 00:39:12.830
is founded on a
lot of those ideas.

00:39:12.830 --> 00:39:14.900
Asian people are other.

00:39:14.900 --> 00:39:17.210
Black people are subservient.

00:39:17.210 --> 00:39:19.760
When you mess with
those ideas, man,

00:39:19.760 --> 00:39:21.310
people do not like hearing it.

00:39:21.310 --> 00:39:24.460
And when you see
how that goes, man.

00:39:24.460 --> 00:39:30.730
You know, I saw-- I went
back home to Minnesota

00:39:30.730 --> 00:39:33.780
and I saw a sign that said
"police lives matter."

00:39:33.780 --> 00:39:35.210
And I'm like, you know what?

00:39:35.210 --> 00:39:37.168
There aren't a lot of
black people around here.

00:39:37.168 --> 00:39:39.421
Who are you yelling back at?

00:39:39.421 --> 00:39:40.795
We're in like
Northern Minnesota.

00:39:40.795 --> 00:39:44.362
I'm like, what
are you afraid of?

00:39:44.362 --> 00:39:46.070
And then I realized
though, it's the idea

00:39:46.070 --> 00:39:47.340
that they're yelling back at.

00:39:47.340 --> 00:39:49.714
The idea that somewhere black
lives might matter is like,

00:39:49.714 --> 00:39:50.745
what?

00:39:50.745 --> 00:39:51.370
No, they don't.

00:39:51.370 --> 00:39:53.160
Not as much as mine.

00:39:53.160 --> 00:39:55.920
And so like that, along with
like if you tell some people

00:39:55.920 --> 00:39:57.779
that native people are alive.

00:39:57.779 --> 00:39:58.320
They're here.

00:39:58.320 --> 00:39:59.240
They're thriving.

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:01.820
They're growing.

00:40:01.820 --> 00:40:04.786
Diana earlier today was talking
about how the population

00:40:04.786 --> 00:40:07.460
of Hopis has gone up.

00:40:07.460 --> 00:40:08.052
Why?

00:40:08.052 --> 00:40:10.260
Outside of that we like
doing what makes that happen.

00:40:10.260 --> 00:40:13.029
But it's gone up because we are.

00:40:13.029 --> 00:40:13.570
We're living.

00:40:13.570 --> 00:40:14.670
We're coming back.

00:40:14.670 --> 00:40:15.927
Our languages are coming back.

00:40:15.927 --> 00:40:17.510
The things that have
been talked about

00:40:17.510 --> 00:40:21.280
are like-- they aren't outside
of the realm of possibility.

00:40:21.280 --> 00:40:23.440
What Matika said, people
can learn our languages.

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:27.220
I saw on YouTube, a white
kid speaking Ojibwe.

00:40:27.220 --> 00:40:28.350
It blew my mind.

00:40:28.350 --> 00:40:31.030
He was a polyglot, and
he was just practicing.

00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:31.780
It was amazing.

00:40:31.780 --> 00:40:32.770
It's amazing to see.

00:40:32.770 --> 00:40:35.780
So when you put a bunch of
like silly men who are like no,

00:40:35.780 --> 00:40:37.780
we're just laughing,
joking, having a good time.

00:40:37.780 --> 00:40:38.590
We're not defeated.

00:40:38.590 --> 00:40:39.790
We're not dead.

00:40:39.790 --> 00:40:41.420
We're just like
cracking ourselves up

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:43.280
at our chubby, naked bodies.

00:40:43.280 --> 00:40:47.332
And when you do that,
and people go like,

00:40:47.332 --> 00:40:48.540
natives are not here, though.

00:40:48.540 --> 00:40:49.081
They're dead.

00:40:49.081 --> 00:40:50.060
You know, they're gone.

00:40:50.060 --> 00:40:52.070
And it really messes
with people's heads.

00:40:52.070 --> 00:40:56.084
And it creates this sort of like
needle that just keeps jabbing.

00:40:56.084 --> 00:40:57.750
And the more we do
that, the more people

00:40:57.750 --> 00:40:59.850
are going to have
to pay attention.

00:40:59.850 --> 00:41:02.770
But we have to get
out of it ourselves.

00:41:02.770 --> 00:41:04.400
As native filmmakers,
as native people,

00:41:04.400 --> 00:41:07.147
we have to embrace not
only the same stories

00:41:07.147 --> 00:41:07.980
that have been told.

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:09.240
And we can't just tell
people that we're here.

00:41:09.240 --> 00:41:10.770
But we got to reach across.

00:41:10.770 --> 00:41:13.335
There's something I call
the audacity of genre

00:41:13.335 --> 00:41:14.570
in native cinema.

00:41:14.570 --> 00:41:17.000
That means do like
a buddy cop movie.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:21.280
Do like a teen sex comedy,
like Porky's or American Pie.

00:41:21.280 --> 00:41:23.570
For native filmmakers
out there, I tell people.

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:25.450
I'm like, do like
a sci-fi flick.

00:41:25.450 --> 00:41:26.420
A horror movie.

00:41:26.420 --> 00:41:26.974
Reach across.

00:41:26.974 --> 00:41:29.140
Because we don't have to
perpetuate the stereotypes,

00:41:29.140 --> 00:41:31.654
but we can embrace
archetypes of other stories.

00:41:31.654 --> 00:41:32.320
And that's fine.

00:41:32.320 --> 00:41:33.249
And people can relate.

00:41:33.249 --> 00:41:35.290
Other people will actually
see what you're doing.

00:41:35.290 --> 00:41:36.580
They will see what
your places look like.

00:41:36.580 --> 00:41:37.840
They'll see your homes.

00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:39.970
And it will be on your terms.

00:41:39.970 --> 00:41:45.200
So that's why I do what I do.

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:50.520
I found out recently that the
documentarian, Billy Luther,

00:41:50.520 --> 00:41:54.640
who I have a lot of respect
for, did Miss Navajo.

00:41:54.640 --> 00:41:56.560
The documentary Miss Navajo.

00:41:56.560 --> 00:42:00.450
And I found out he did a
movie called Red Lake, which

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:02.340
one of the things
that I said when

00:42:02.340 --> 00:42:07.562
I was jibbering at you in Ojibwe
was-- ojibberish as we say.

00:42:07.562 --> 00:42:09.020
One of the things
that I was saying

00:42:09.020 --> 00:42:11.800
is that I'm from Red
Lake. [SPEAKING OJIBWE].

00:42:11.800 --> 00:42:14.350
That means I'm from Red Lake.

00:42:14.350 --> 00:42:17.910
And so like when I saw that
he was doing documentary,

00:42:17.910 --> 00:42:19.330
I was like, hell yeah, man.

00:42:19.330 --> 00:42:20.490
A native dude's
doing a documentary

00:42:20.490 --> 00:42:21.090
about where I'm from.

00:42:21.090 --> 00:42:21.890
That's awesome.

00:42:21.890 --> 00:42:24.216
Because you know, Red Lake
has this complex issue

00:42:24.216 --> 00:42:24.840
of sovereignty.

00:42:24.840 --> 00:42:26.756
There are certain treaties
that we didn't sign

00:42:26.756 --> 00:42:28.220
and it gives us a
lot of autonomy.

00:42:28.220 --> 00:42:29.944
And I was like,
oh, that's great.

00:42:29.944 --> 00:42:31.110
What's it going to be about?

00:42:31.110 --> 00:42:34.170
And I look it up and Red Lake
is about a school shooting,

00:42:34.170 --> 00:42:36.730
and about how our people
are sad but still proud.

00:42:36.730 --> 00:42:39.120
And I was like, well, fuck.

00:42:39.120 --> 00:42:42.390
So that is the kind
of thing-- that's

00:42:42.390 --> 00:42:46.330
the reason that we do
what we do, to change

00:42:46.330 --> 00:42:47.413
that narrative completely.

00:42:50.370 --> 00:42:53.262
Because you know, I ain't
trying to burn down America.

00:42:53.262 --> 00:42:56.840
But I mean, I might be trying
to make it great again.

00:42:56.840 --> 00:43:00.886
[APPLAUSE]

00:43:00.886 --> 00:43:01.385
Thanks.

00:43:13.550 --> 00:43:14.612
-Oh my goodness.

00:43:17.330 --> 00:43:22.520
So I don't have any talent
like Irene and Migizi.

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:23.310
True story.

00:43:23.310 --> 00:43:25.680
I took acting classes
in Los Angeles,

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:29.060
and the director kept saying,
you know, on Wednesday night

00:43:29.060 --> 00:43:32.590
we have script writing.

00:43:32.590 --> 00:43:35.290
So needless to say,
I'm going to talk

00:43:35.290 --> 00:43:40.870
about infrastructure today,
just bring you back to reality.

00:43:40.870 --> 00:43:42.815
I need the little
remote thing here.

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:49.600
So I want to first start
off by a quick introduction.

00:43:49.600 --> 00:43:51.850
I come from the
village of Oraibi,

00:43:51.850 --> 00:43:56.920
that Diane Judge Humetewa
mentioned this morning.

00:43:56.920 --> 00:44:02.120
It's a village that has no
running water, no telephone

00:44:02.120 --> 00:44:04.440
service.

00:44:04.440 --> 00:44:09.290
And when I was younger,
we didn't even have radio.

00:44:09.290 --> 00:44:10.450
No television.

00:44:10.450 --> 00:44:11.700
Of course, I mentioned that.

00:44:11.700 --> 00:44:13.500
And no broadband.

00:44:13.500 --> 00:44:18.030
And so years later, I've
now become an advocate

00:44:18.030 --> 00:44:22.710
for the digital and media
divide in this country

00:44:22.710 --> 00:44:24.660
that is so wide.

00:44:24.660 --> 00:44:27.510
And someone once said to
me, they said, dang, Loris.

00:44:27.510 --> 00:44:29.810
You're really over-qualified.

00:44:29.810 --> 00:44:32.720
You're like the poster child.

00:44:32.720 --> 00:44:35.110
So I want to take
you on this journey

00:44:35.110 --> 00:44:41.880
and just remind you why media
matters in this country.

00:44:41.880 --> 00:44:46.300
Media access,
control, and ownership

00:44:46.300 --> 00:44:49.005
is really, quite frankly,
about power and position.

00:44:51.520 --> 00:44:54.490
Seeking power and
position over others

00:44:54.490 --> 00:44:57.770
is embedded in human cultures.

00:44:57.770 --> 00:45:01.920
We build institutions and
systems of administration

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:04.960
and we predicate
this on formulas

00:45:04.960 --> 00:45:08.520
that have evolved from
cultural imbalances, which

00:45:08.520 --> 00:45:14.320
includes hierarchy,
imperialism, and so forth.

00:45:14.320 --> 00:45:17.550
Whoever is in power
gets to tell their story

00:45:17.550 --> 00:45:20.020
through their optics and lens.

00:45:20.020 --> 00:45:24.757
And they often do this to
justify their own power

00:45:24.757 --> 00:45:25.340
and existence.

00:45:31.300 --> 00:45:34.380
So I love this map.

00:45:34.380 --> 00:45:36.710
Media access,
control, and ownership

00:45:36.710 --> 00:45:40.690
is also about ownership capital.

00:45:40.690 --> 00:45:45.930
There's a perpetual pursuit
of capital or the ownership

00:45:45.930 --> 00:45:49.670
and competitive
acquisition of resources.

00:45:49.670 --> 00:45:55.620
We do this through titles, how
we acquire spaces and places.

00:45:55.620 --> 00:45:59.450
And this includes our
airwaves spectrum, including

00:45:59.450 --> 00:46:04.570
radio and television
frequencies are no exception.

00:46:04.570 --> 00:46:07.310
It pretty much is
like land and water,

00:46:07.310 --> 00:46:10.435
except that we got into
the fight much later.

00:46:17.250 --> 00:46:20.970
In most major markets, like
Phoenix or Minneapolis,

00:46:20.970 --> 00:46:25.970
and in the commercial
broadcast environment,

00:46:25.970 --> 00:46:28.320
radio and television
ownership is

00:46:28.320 --> 00:46:32.670
held by major commercial
conglomerates.

00:46:32.670 --> 00:46:38.460
Consolidated media ownership is
a huge problem in this country.

00:46:38.460 --> 00:46:43.750
Native Public Media did a small
market study of Albuquerque

00:46:43.750 --> 00:46:47.750
about, I would
say, six years ago.

00:46:47.750 --> 00:46:54.210
And out of 52 stations
that existed in that town,

00:46:54.210 --> 00:46:59.780
only 1 station dedicated any
hours of native programming

00:46:59.780 --> 00:47:03.840
to the communities that
surrounded them-- KUNM.

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:06.280
Look it up.

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:12.120
Very sad when New Mexico
has quite a large number

00:47:12.120 --> 00:47:16.320
of Native American tribes
within its boundaries.

00:47:19.890 --> 00:47:23.110
Media access,
control, and ownership

00:47:23.110 --> 00:47:27.370
is really important to
overcoming intolerance,

00:47:27.370 --> 00:47:30.830
stereotypes that everyone
has mentioned today.

00:47:30.830 --> 00:47:34.490
And really, just
patronizing Native Americans

00:47:34.490 --> 00:47:40.440
in this country, which
is still going on today.

00:47:40.440 --> 00:47:44.120
Without media access,
control, and ownership,

00:47:44.120 --> 00:47:48.580
we cannot fully acknowledge
the injustices of the past

00:47:48.580 --> 00:47:51.200
on our own terms.

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:55.360
And so this is really
what drives my work.

00:47:55.360 --> 00:47:58.030
By having our own
broadcast facilities,

00:47:58.030 --> 00:48:02.830
we begin to actively value
the rich cultural diversity

00:48:02.830 --> 00:48:06.980
among tribes in the
context and structures

00:48:06.980 --> 00:48:11.400
of our most exalted
institutions economically,

00:48:11.400 --> 00:48:15.780
socially, culturally,
and educationally.

00:48:15.780 --> 00:48:18.850
A few years back,
Native Public Media

00:48:18.850 --> 00:48:24.080
served as an advisor to a
major public service media

00:48:24.080 --> 00:48:27.390
institution in the
Boston area, WGBH.

00:48:27.390 --> 00:48:29.480
You may have heard of them.

00:48:29.480 --> 00:48:32.710
We helped to produce
four major films.

00:48:32.710 --> 00:48:35.470
And for the life of me, I
can only remember three.

00:48:35.470 --> 00:48:39.525
They included Wounded Knee,
Geronimo, and The Mayflower.

00:48:42.510 --> 00:48:46.360
Now, I had to include
this because there's

00:48:46.360 --> 00:48:50.750
a continuing romantic notion
about Native Americans.

00:48:50.750 --> 00:48:53.530
It's sort of that
Fabio effect that

00:48:53.530 --> 00:48:58.390
continues to be present today.

00:48:58.390 --> 00:49:00.850
Media access, control,
and ownership,

00:49:00.850 --> 00:49:04.130
it's about parity
and justice as well.

00:49:04.130 --> 00:49:07.250
In modern America, the
revolution is not over.

00:49:07.250 --> 00:49:11.330
And in fact, it's just
beginning for Indian country.

00:49:11.330 --> 00:49:17.650
It strikes this closed-offness.

00:49:17.650 --> 00:49:20.360
Or, I would say, the
censorship of voices

00:49:20.360 --> 00:49:23.900
that ought to be heard,
really strikes to the heart

00:49:23.900 --> 00:49:25.520
of the First Amendment.

00:49:25.520 --> 00:49:29.520
It strikes to the heart
of our freedom to speak,

00:49:29.520 --> 00:49:34.840
the freedom of the press,
and the freedom to be heard.

00:49:34.840 --> 00:49:37.900
And let me just
give you an example.

00:49:37.900 --> 00:49:44.190
A few years back,
not too long ago,

00:49:44.190 --> 00:49:51.990
the Arizona State legislature
passed Arizona House Bill 2281,

00:49:51.990 --> 00:49:56.210
which was really to silence
and censor the ethnic voices

00:49:56.210 --> 00:49:58.016
within the state of Arizona.

00:50:00.610 --> 00:50:06.140
And what it does is that
it prohibits ethnic studies

00:50:06.140 --> 00:50:12.520
in schools that are funded by
the state and makes it illegal,

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:13.020
in fact.

00:50:15.530 --> 00:50:19.570
This is quite disturbing
because Arizona is home

00:50:19.570 --> 00:50:22.790
to 22 tribal nations.

00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:26.780
One of the states that has
the largest native populations

00:50:26.780 --> 00:50:29.570
in this country.

00:50:29.570 --> 00:50:34.500
When we have the power to
access, control, and own

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:37.620
our own media facility,
we are actively

00:50:37.620 --> 00:50:41.870
working towards the full
recognition of the impact

00:50:41.870 --> 00:50:44.180
of our own history.

00:50:44.180 --> 00:50:48.700
We are able to assess our role
and place in the hierarchy

00:50:48.700 --> 00:50:51.660
of power and control.

00:50:51.660 --> 00:50:56.780
And we can optimize our
personal and professional energy

00:50:56.780 --> 00:50:59.640
to tell our own stories.

00:50:59.640 --> 00:51:03.505
And also, look out for our
own wellness and happiness.

00:51:06.350 --> 00:51:09.040
Media access,
control, and ownership

00:51:09.040 --> 00:51:12.090
is about being our own
stewards and guardians

00:51:12.090 --> 00:51:13.950
of our own freedom.

00:51:13.950 --> 00:51:19.870
Now, Sherman Alexie is a
record holder of banned books.

00:51:19.870 --> 00:51:21.960
He held it in 2014.

00:51:21.960 --> 00:51:27.090
And if you look it up today,
he's holding it in 2016.

00:51:27.090 --> 00:51:33.160
And the reasons for banning
his books range from the fact

00:51:33.160 --> 00:51:36.850
that he's like writing
about insidious stuff

00:51:36.850 --> 00:51:40.120
that could harm
society, like murder

00:51:40.120 --> 00:51:43.740
and violence and rude language.

00:51:43.740 --> 00:51:46.154
And so I thought about that.

00:51:46.154 --> 00:51:48.310
I used to teach at a
little-known school

00:51:48.310 --> 00:51:52.100
just a short distance from
here, Phillips Exeter Academy.

00:51:52.100 --> 00:51:55.040
You may have heard of it.

00:51:55.040 --> 00:51:57.750
And I remember that
one of our textbooks

00:51:57.750 --> 00:52:01.530
was quite Shakespearean
in nature.

00:52:01.530 --> 00:52:03.470
And I was thinking, like, wow.

00:52:03.470 --> 00:52:04.840
All these elements.

00:52:04.840 --> 00:52:07.080
I think I remember
those stories.

00:52:07.080 --> 00:52:09.275
And I was thinking,
like Romeo and Juliet.

00:52:11.970 --> 00:52:16.710
So there's really no rhyme
or reason to the reasons

00:52:16.710 --> 00:52:19.180
why he continues to
be on a banned book.

00:52:19.180 --> 00:52:23.820
But it does drive me to go out
and buy copies of his books

00:52:23.820 --> 00:52:24.675
for all my friends.

00:52:27.450 --> 00:52:29.610
Media access,
control, and ownership

00:52:29.610 --> 00:52:33.780
is understanding and
exercising our own power.

00:52:33.780 --> 00:52:38.960
Media is based on an unshakable
consciousness of superiority,

00:52:38.960 --> 00:52:42.470
imperial conquest
and colonization,

00:52:42.470 --> 00:52:46.930
and it's directly linked to
information, social structures,

00:52:46.930 --> 00:52:52.490
media messages, and
educational curriculum.

00:52:52.490 --> 00:52:56.380
When I started my
work back in 2004,

00:52:56.380 --> 00:53:00.070
I read about all
the 10 commissioned

00:53:00.070 --> 00:53:04.380
studies by the Federal
Communications Commission.

00:53:04.380 --> 00:53:09.680
And what I learned was that the
commission saw Native Americans

00:53:09.680 --> 00:53:14.290
through the optics of that
we were vulnerable, unserved,

00:53:14.290 --> 00:53:19.470
under-served, and probably
the most fragile and invisible

00:53:19.470 --> 00:53:20.706
in the United States.

00:53:23.520 --> 00:53:29.240
So I wanted to do
something about that

00:53:29.240 --> 00:53:31.590
because media access,
control, and ownership

00:53:31.590 --> 00:53:33.760
is really about
the power to speak

00:53:33.760 --> 00:53:35.730
and the power to be heard.

00:53:35.730 --> 00:53:38.760
It's about our affirmation
of our identity.

00:53:38.760 --> 00:53:40.730
It's about cultural survival.

00:53:40.730 --> 00:53:44.390
It's about native language
programming, cultural content,

00:53:44.390 --> 00:53:46.530
history, and localism.

00:53:46.530 --> 00:53:49.500
And it's an exercise of
our tribal sovereignty

00:53:49.500 --> 00:53:52.020
and self-determination.

00:53:52.020 --> 00:53:54.670
One of the things that we
do from Native Public Media

00:53:54.670 --> 00:53:57.900
is to host a one-week
high school boot

00:53:57.900 --> 00:54:01.460
camp in communications
for young people.

00:54:01.460 --> 00:54:04.220
And we immerse them in
television and radio

00:54:04.220 --> 00:54:07.170
and different platforms
on the internet.

00:54:07.170 --> 00:54:10.989
And what we want to do is build
capacity across Indian country.

00:54:16.150 --> 00:54:22.040
Native Public Media since
2004 has helped tribes

00:54:22.040 --> 00:54:25.720
to bring broadcast
facilities to Indian country.

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:27.400
And our work is just beginning.

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:29.390
We're not done.

00:54:29.390 --> 00:54:33.410
In our network, we
have 58 radio stations,

00:54:33.410 --> 00:54:36.260
3 terrestrial
television stations.

00:54:36.260 --> 00:54:40.350
We do everything from high-power
to low-power broadcast

00:54:40.350 --> 00:54:45.070
facilities, AM/FM, public
service media, commercial,

00:54:45.070 --> 00:54:46.186
and now digital.

00:54:48.880 --> 00:54:55.210
Because if we want to
stand on our own two feet,

00:54:55.210 --> 00:54:59.630
we need to work against
being silenced by rules

00:54:59.630 --> 00:55:02.080
and regulations and laws.

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:07.020
We need to make sure that there
is engagement, consultation,

00:55:07.020 --> 00:55:09.430
and that we overcome
invisibility

00:55:09.430 --> 00:55:13.280
and the "other" box.

00:55:13.280 --> 00:55:18.130
Freedom is part of
the process in terms

00:55:18.130 --> 00:55:20.280
of media access and ownership.

00:55:20.280 --> 00:55:24.360
It's a validation
of who you are.

00:55:24.360 --> 00:55:26.430
We can write our own history.

00:55:26.430 --> 00:55:30.090
And the modern pen
are the channels

00:55:30.090 --> 00:55:33.750
that we exercise
control over, which

00:55:33.750 --> 00:55:35.458
includes broadcast facilities.

00:55:39.350 --> 00:55:41.360
And one of the
fundamental questions

00:55:41.360 --> 00:55:45.840
we have to ask ourselves
is, whose democracy is it?

00:55:48.590 --> 00:55:55.210
To overcome and to in part
answer this question, in 2010

00:55:55.210 --> 00:55:59.660
we worked for a tribal
priority for broadcasting.

00:55:59.660 --> 00:56:03.090
Not because we were
minorities in this country,

00:56:03.090 --> 00:56:06.390
but because we come from
sovereign governments,

00:56:06.390 --> 00:56:10.590
and that flows into
our individualism

00:56:10.590 --> 00:56:12.133
as tribal members.

00:56:14.830 --> 00:56:19.470
We also established in 2010,
the FCC Office of Native Affairs

00:56:19.470 --> 00:56:20.640
and Policy.

00:56:20.640 --> 00:56:22.450
And when we first
floated the idea,

00:56:22.450 --> 00:56:26.140
we talked about a
native desk at the FCC.

00:56:26.140 --> 00:56:28.340
And after it was vetted
by tribal leaders,

00:56:28.340 --> 00:56:30.880
they basically said,
we don't want a desk.

00:56:30.880 --> 00:56:35.360
We want an office staffed
with economists, and analysts,

00:56:35.360 --> 00:56:40.580
and lawyers, and
engineers to do this work.

00:56:40.580 --> 00:56:42.960
We also submitted
recommendations

00:56:42.960 --> 00:56:47.230
that were included in the
National Broadband Plan.

00:56:47.230 --> 00:56:54.300
But having to work with 567
native nations in this country,

00:56:54.300 --> 00:56:55.520
it's going to take a lot.

00:56:55.520 --> 00:56:56.950
A lot more work.

00:56:56.950 --> 00:57:01.190
We've just barely
taken the first steps.

00:57:01.190 --> 00:57:05.570
Last year, we included in
the Stafford Act of FEMA

00:57:05.570 --> 00:57:08.850
the inclusion of
broadcast facilities

00:57:08.850 --> 00:57:12.980
for emergency recognition.

00:57:12.980 --> 00:57:16.340
And technology has
changed the landscape,

00:57:16.340 --> 00:57:19.670
broadband in particular.

00:57:19.670 --> 00:57:23.020
But across Indian
country, back in 2004,

00:57:23.020 --> 00:57:26.340
broadband penetration
was at 10%,

00:57:26.340 --> 00:57:30.760
which meant that 90% of
Indian country was dark.

00:57:30.760 --> 00:57:34.850
Now we've worked really
hard to close that gap.

00:57:34.850 --> 00:57:37.570
And I think we've inched
up, but we don't really

00:57:37.570 --> 00:57:40.240
have any hard data
to prove that.

00:57:40.240 --> 00:57:43.590
The FCC said perhaps
we're around 25%

00:57:43.590 --> 00:57:45.560
penetration at this point.

00:57:48.120 --> 00:57:54.640
And so it's a reminder of
the long road ahead of us,

00:57:54.640 --> 00:57:58.760
but we have a lot to
celebrate as well.

00:57:58.760 --> 00:58:03.880
On April 20, we celebrated
Hiller River Broadcast

00:58:03.880 --> 00:58:11.040
Corporation, the first
commercial low-power digital

00:58:11.040 --> 00:58:15.110
television station serving
a tribal community.

00:58:15.110 --> 00:58:17.740
And that was in Arizona.

00:58:17.740 --> 00:58:23.720
On April 21st and 22nd,
we celebrated the National

00:58:23.720 --> 00:58:27.250
Broadcast Summit, bringing
together about 70 broadcasters

00:58:27.250 --> 00:58:30.580
from Indian country,
to share our stories

00:58:30.580 --> 00:58:34.200
around emergency preparedness
communications, which

00:58:34.200 --> 00:58:37.650
followed on the heels
of a one week training

00:58:37.650 --> 00:58:41.750
on the FEMA ground
in Anniston, Alabama.

00:58:41.750 --> 00:58:46.060
And what I basically learned
is that communications

00:58:46.060 --> 00:58:50.130
is a fundamental human right.

00:58:50.130 --> 00:58:54.470
And that we have to work
to make sure that we

00:58:54.470 --> 00:58:59.520
continue to have media access,
control, and ownership.

00:58:59.520 --> 00:59:03.420
We may be the fastest growing
network in the country,

00:59:03.420 --> 00:59:07.020
but we still have
a long ways to go.

00:59:07.020 --> 00:59:08.760
And I'm so happy to be here.

00:59:08.760 --> 00:59:14.480
I want to thank Dean Elizabeth
Cohen, Danielle Carpenter,

00:59:14.480 --> 00:59:18.030
and Shelly Lowe,
and the organizers

00:59:18.030 --> 00:59:19.670
of this fantastic conference.

00:59:19.670 --> 00:59:21.520
I've learned a lot.

00:59:21.520 --> 00:59:25.290
I hope to take it back
with me to my community.

00:59:25.290 --> 00:59:28.600
And I look forward to a
long term partnership.

00:59:28.600 --> 00:59:33.850
We need some academics in
native public media circle.

00:59:33.850 --> 00:59:37.190
We can use your help to
move this movement forward.

00:59:37.190 --> 00:59:41.180
Someone once said, it's not
about talking to the choir,

00:59:41.180 --> 00:59:43.980
it's about talking to
those individuals that

00:59:43.980 --> 00:59:46.630
don't necessarily
disagree with you,

00:59:46.630 --> 00:59:50.440
but who may in some
instances, wholeheartedly,

00:59:50.440 --> 00:59:52.320
agree with your position.

00:59:52.320 --> 00:59:55.280
But if you can move
them in your direction,

00:59:55.280 --> 00:59:57.610
then that's the work
ahead of us. [NON-ENGLISH]

