-Thank you so much.

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:15.160
You are amazing, panel.

01:00:15.160 --> 01:00:16.930
And we have brought
the microphone

01:00:16.930 --> 01:00:18.840
to the center of
the room, if anyone

01:00:18.840 --> 01:00:20.980
has questions for the panel.

01:00:23.550 --> 01:00:26.050
If you don't, I have
a whole list, as well.

01:00:29.331 --> 01:00:29.830
-Hi.

01:00:29.830 --> 01:00:31.900
Thank you so much for
your presentations.

01:00:31.900 --> 01:00:34.870
It's very inspiring
to be here today.

01:00:34.870 --> 01:00:38.170
I have a quick question
about the exoticism

01:00:38.170 --> 01:00:40.620
that people of color,
or marginalized people,

01:00:40.620 --> 01:00:42.070
still experience.

01:00:42.070 --> 01:00:43.570
I think a lot of
people in this room

01:00:43.570 --> 01:00:46.170
can attest to the experience
of when someone meets you

01:00:46.170 --> 01:00:47.450
and they ask, what are you?

01:00:47.450 --> 01:00:48.680
Where are you from?

01:00:48.680 --> 01:00:50.130
And it's hard.

01:00:50.130 --> 01:00:52.120
We have such
complex genealogies.

01:00:52.120 --> 01:00:54.430
There's no fixed geography.

01:00:54.430 --> 01:00:56.910
We can trace our roots all over.

01:00:56.910 --> 01:01:00.290
So I just want to know
professionally, artistically,

01:01:00.290 --> 01:01:06.950
personally, how do you
confront and continue

01:01:06.950 --> 01:01:11.090
to deconstruct
the exoticism that

01:01:11.090 --> 01:01:16.670
is still placed
on people of color

01:01:16.670 --> 01:01:20.180
in the arts and entertainment?

01:01:20.180 --> 01:01:26.200
And if so, if you
feel like it's still

01:01:26.200 --> 01:01:29.392
kind of an uphill battle
for your work and when

01:01:29.392 --> 01:01:30.975
you're about to
attempt a new project?

01:01:33.650 --> 01:01:34.800
-Sure.

01:01:34.800 --> 01:01:35.910
Go ahead.

01:01:39.610 --> 01:01:41.315
-I have that story, too.

01:01:44.190 --> 01:01:48.970
It got so when I left and
was in Philadelphia, where

01:01:48.970 --> 01:01:54.365
I went to university, I started
just asking people to guess,

01:01:54.365 --> 01:01:58.308
for that what are you.

01:01:58.308 --> 01:02:00.540
It got to this point where
the sort of quip answer,

01:02:00.540 --> 01:02:03.300
like I'm a human being.

01:02:03.300 --> 01:02:06.705
But then people
never would guess.

01:02:06.705 --> 01:02:08.080
They would guess
everything else.

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:11.940
And then when they did find
out, their eyes lit up,

01:02:11.940 --> 01:02:15.060
and it was, for me, one of
the first times of realizing

01:02:15.060 --> 01:02:19.170
just how amazing we
are, our cultures are,

01:02:19.170 --> 01:02:21.270
and how people want to know.

01:02:21.270 --> 01:02:26.585
And so I always try to approach
things from being an ambassador

01:02:26.585 --> 01:02:29.050
or being a teacher.

01:02:29.050 --> 01:02:33.850
But at the same time,
I think that it's

01:02:33.850 --> 01:02:39.960
that other that we are
discussing that I think

01:02:39.960 --> 01:02:42.700
causes this separation,
or this feeling

01:02:42.700 --> 01:02:46.300
that you are not a human being.

01:02:46.300 --> 01:02:51.810
That there's a way to kind
of objectify you as a person.

01:02:51.810 --> 01:02:53.250
And so, it's really
just a matter

01:02:53.250 --> 01:03:00.280
of helping people to see the
complexities of us, of who

01:03:00.280 --> 01:03:01.020
we are.

01:03:01.020 --> 01:03:06.390
And that first and foremost,
we're human beings.

01:03:06.390 --> 01:03:08.820
-Yeah.

01:03:08.820 --> 01:03:10.580
So yeah, I've gotten
the same question.

01:03:10.580 --> 01:03:16.570
And especially, because I'm
short haired, and whatever,

01:03:16.570 --> 01:03:20.750
so I'm not obviously
native to a lot of folks.

01:03:20.750 --> 01:03:23.914
And I got to a
point, same thing,

01:03:23.914 --> 01:03:25.830
I went totally the
opposite direction, though.

01:03:25.830 --> 01:03:27.760
She's talking about,
I'm a human being.

01:03:27.760 --> 01:03:30.220
And I think that I've
used up my swears, too,

01:03:30.220 --> 01:03:31.730
so I'm not going
to say it, but I

01:03:31.730 --> 01:03:36.160
said I usually say like I'm
f-ing awesome, what are you?

01:03:36.160 --> 01:03:37.680
Or whatever.

01:03:37.680 --> 01:03:40.260
I'm just too damn good looking.

01:03:40.260 --> 01:03:43.480
So like it opens a dialogue.

01:03:43.480 --> 01:03:47.320
I combat things with humor
as much as I can the way.

01:03:47.320 --> 01:03:49.310
I think when you
make somebody laugh,

01:03:49.310 --> 01:03:50.570
it builds a little bridge.

01:03:50.570 --> 01:03:55.100
And you're like, all right,
well, let's talk as people now.

01:03:55.100 --> 01:03:57.890
I can't, obviously, I can't--
none of us can speak for all

01:03:57.890 --> 01:04:01.370
POCM, talking about much
of a battle is left.

01:04:01.370 --> 01:04:02.755
And it's forever, man.

01:04:02.755 --> 01:04:04.380
And we're always
going to be struggling

01:04:04.380 --> 01:04:06.009
to understand each other.

01:04:06.009 --> 01:04:08.550
But the best thing is, I think
just to be secure in yourself,

01:04:08.550 --> 01:04:10.470
and hope that the
other person is, too

01:04:10.470 --> 01:04:12.580
and you guys can
have a dialogue, so.

01:04:15.460 --> 01:04:17.036
-Perfectly done.

01:04:17.036 --> 01:04:17.952
-Thank you, very much.

01:04:21.730 --> 01:04:22.626
-Hello.

01:04:22.626 --> 01:04:23.920
Kelly Dennis.

01:04:23.920 --> 01:04:25.495
I'm an attorney.

01:04:25.495 --> 01:04:28.760
I'm a tribal member of the
Shinnecock nation, also

01:04:28.760 --> 01:04:32.720
[INAUDIBLE] Nipmuc, from here.

01:04:32.720 --> 01:04:37.690
I was sent to Catholic
school for most

01:04:37.690 --> 01:04:39.360
of my-- up until eighth grade.

01:04:39.360 --> 01:04:41.790
And every year, they'd have
like these crazy plays.

01:04:41.790 --> 01:04:43.490
And we always play something.

01:04:43.490 --> 01:04:45.680
And it'd be something the
nuns would put together.

01:04:45.680 --> 01:04:51.510
And there would be
this one time where

01:04:51.510 --> 01:04:55.154
my mother, she would always
love to-- she's an artist,

01:04:55.154 --> 01:04:56.820
so she would love to
do the backgrounds.

01:04:56.820 --> 01:04:58.790
And she got so
excited this one year

01:04:58.790 --> 01:05:05.010
when we were going to
have, a portion of it

01:05:05.010 --> 01:05:09.530
would be to have the Native
Americans, I don't even know,

01:05:09.530 --> 01:05:10.250
I was so young.

01:05:10.250 --> 01:05:12.940
I must have been like
seven or eight years old.

01:05:12.940 --> 01:05:15.760
Anyway, I remember having
like these like glow

01:05:15.760 --> 01:05:19.380
in the dark like sprinkle things
that you like twirl around.

01:05:19.380 --> 01:05:22.360
And there would be like
tipis and things like that.

01:05:22.360 --> 01:05:26.470
And then I look back on it,
and I'm like what in the world

01:05:26.470 --> 01:05:28.760
did we do?

01:05:28.760 --> 01:05:32.290
And then, again,
it was in a way,

01:05:32.290 --> 01:05:35.370
it was conflicting,
because I still

01:05:35.370 --> 01:05:41.800
kind of felt a weird pride
in it, because at least they

01:05:41.800 --> 01:05:44.800
were acknowledging
that there were natives

01:05:44.800 --> 01:05:47.890
in this Catholic school, even
though they were portraying us

01:05:47.890 --> 01:05:51.410
so wrongly and with the
tipi and these weird glow

01:05:51.410 --> 01:05:53.230
in the dark things.

01:05:53.230 --> 01:05:58.130
And then I remember that she,
a few years down the line,

01:05:58.130 --> 01:06:01.890
I think she wised
up and they tried

01:06:01.890 --> 01:06:04.980
to put on a play of Peter Pan.

01:06:04.980 --> 01:06:07.900
And then, she was
like, wait a minute,

01:06:07.900 --> 01:06:10.950
now they're just
going to be equating

01:06:10.950 --> 01:06:15.030
the kids from the reservation as
basically the mermaids in Peter

01:06:15.030 --> 01:06:15.530
Pan.

01:06:15.530 --> 01:06:17.270
And they're so fantastical.

01:06:17.270 --> 01:06:18.730
And I was just
wondering, I think

01:06:18.730 --> 01:06:22.140
that maybe one of the
latest things that I think

01:06:22.140 --> 01:06:27.850
I've heard of was if
they do do Peter Pan,

01:06:27.850 --> 01:06:29.860
kind of like the
Disney thing or not,

01:06:29.860 --> 01:06:32.010
who would portray Tiger Lily?

01:06:32.010 --> 01:06:35.510
Is it appropriate that they
cast a Native American woman

01:06:35.510 --> 01:06:36.490
in that?

01:06:36.490 --> 01:06:40.170
And I was just wondering
your thoughts on that.

01:06:40.170 --> 01:06:41.170
-Thank you.

01:06:46.341 --> 01:06:48.340
-So I think we can even
take it a little broader

01:06:48.340 --> 01:06:50.810
and think about
that role of casting

01:06:50.810 --> 01:06:54.350
of native peoples in
very stereotypical roles,

01:06:54.350 --> 01:06:56.320
and what your thoughts
are about that.

01:06:56.320 --> 01:06:58.080
Should we be embracing
that or should we

01:06:58.080 --> 01:07:00.880
be moving away from it?

01:07:00.880 --> 01:07:02.680
-If you think of that
Night at the Museum

01:07:02.680 --> 01:07:14.600
or-- I mean I think that because
these are there-- and just

01:07:14.600 --> 01:07:20.560
my own experience, I do know
that I would never understand

01:07:20.560 --> 01:07:23.670
really, honestly when
people would meet me

01:07:23.670 --> 01:07:29.340
and would burst into tears
until I met Buffy Sainte-Marie.

01:07:29.340 --> 01:07:31.200
She had the Creative
Board Teaching Project

01:07:31.200 --> 01:07:32.670
and she asked if I
would be a part of it.

01:07:32.670 --> 01:07:33.260
And I went.

01:07:33.260 --> 01:07:38.190
And they screened some things
from Sesame Street beforehand.

01:07:38.190 --> 01:07:40.820
And when I met her,
I burst into tears

01:07:40.820 --> 01:07:45.070
because I realized
she was the only image

01:07:45.070 --> 01:07:48.620
of a Native American
woman, positive image,

01:07:48.620 --> 01:07:50.690
that I ever saw growing up.

01:07:50.690 --> 01:07:54.180
And I kind of went, oh, OK.

01:07:54.180 --> 01:07:56.620
I understand this
now a little more.

01:07:56.620 --> 01:08:01.280
I think that we get so
starving, and starved,

01:08:01.280 --> 01:08:07.890
for just anyone up there so
that you can look up, look out,

01:08:07.890 --> 01:08:13.090
into this screen of the world
and feel like that's me,

01:08:13.090 --> 01:08:19.359
or that's some reflection of
my experience, and who I am.

01:08:19.359 --> 01:08:26.109
And you know so it's
such a difficult world

01:08:26.109 --> 01:08:30.902
to be a part of as far as
on this side of the camera.

01:08:35.800 --> 01:08:36.670
I mean, I was lucky.

01:08:36.670 --> 01:08:42.890
I was able to make a living
at doing what I did-- do.

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:48.910
But at the same
time, you're handed

01:08:48.910 --> 01:08:51.430
what I explained in your hand.

01:08:51.430 --> 01:08:57.200
So I would never-- I
would always feel positive

01:08:57.200 --> 01:09:02.830
about that native woman who
would take that role on, yet

01:09:02.830 --> 01:09:07.979
at the same time I would work
diligently to create more three

01:09:07.979 --> 01:09:13.939
dimensional human women
characters, and men, too.

01:09:13.939 --> 01:09:16.960
All of us, we just
don't get that chance,

01:09:16.960 --> 01:09:23.350
so I would never feel
negatively toward that.

01:09:23.350 --> 01:09:26.810
-I have a slightly
different perspective.

01:09:26.810 --> 01:09:30.000
I think in order to
change the narrative.

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:34.319
And if we're serious about the
roles that are stereotypical,

01:09:34.319 --> 01:09:38.000
or those that are
demeaning, or unflavorful

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:41.090
to Native Americans, we
have to draw the line.

01:09:41.090 --> 01:09:44.870
Otherwise, we're complicit.

01:09:44.870 --> 01:09:48.010
One of the reasons why
Native Public Media sought

01:09:48.010 --> 01:09:51.220
to build facilities
across Indian country

01:09:51.220 --> 01:09:55.740
was to provide a channel where
we could tell our own stories.

01:09:55.740 --> 01:10:03.870
And so, I've seen actors
stand up, walk off,

01:10:03.870 --> 01:10:07.940
movie sets because
they felt very strongly

01:10:07.940 --> 01:10:11.480
that the depictions
of Native Americans

01:10:11.480 --> 01:10:16.770
was not favorable
to Indian country.

01:10:16.770 --> 01:10:21.840
And I think, just my
personal views on the matter,

01:10:21.840 --> 01:10:24.270
to change the course
of history, you

01:10:24.270 --> 01:10:26.040
have to break the tie somewhere.

01:10:29.790 --> 01:10:30.610
-No way.

01:10:33.980 --> 01:10:38.330
Tiger Lily would have to be
completely ripped apart, taken

01:10:38.330 --> 01:10:40.770
down, deconstructed.

01:10:40.770 --> 01:10:44.770
A part one of the stereotypes
is the Indian maiden.

01:10:44.770 --> 01:10:47.000
And the Indian maiden,
one of her main roles

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:52.660
is to, again, with the
cultivating the wilderness,

01:10:52.660 --> 01:10:54.850
conquering the wilderness,
one of her main roles

01:10:54.850 --> 01:10:56.391
is to be accessible
to the white guy.

01:10:56.391 --> 01:10:58.710
She's never accessible
to her own people.

01:10:58.710 --> 01:11:04.230
And so a lot of native women
roles, they do the same thing.

01:11:04.230 --> 01:11:07.680
They're don't have a
romantic involvement at all

01:11:07.680 --> 01:11:10.370
with any of the characters.

01:11:10.370 --> 01:11:13.780
I'm not saying that they need to
have only romantic involvement.

01:11:13.780 --> 01:11:17.290
But in that kind of narrative,
it only exists for that

01:11:17.290 --> 01:11:20.080
and I think unless she's like
sitting there, sword in hand,

01:11:20.080 --> 01:11:22.590
and her only thing is to fight
side-by-side with Peter Pan

01:11:22.590 --> 01:11:24.006
and conquer the
hell out of things

01:11:24.006 --> 01:11:25.450
and then go back to her people.

01:11:25.450 --> 01:11:29.437
That would be a better story,
but outside of that no, no.

01:11:29.437 --> 01:11:29.937
Sorry.

01:11:33.840 --> 01:11:34.750
-Hi.

01:11:34.750 --> 01:11:35.630
My name is Sierra.

01:11:35.630 --> 01:11:39.770
I'm a second year student
at Brown University.

01:11:39.770 --> 01:11:45.140
And one of my questions that
I was thinking about-- oh,

01:11:45.140 --> 01:11:49.850
first of all, thank you all for
speaking, it was really great.

01:11:49.850 --> 01:11:52.660
The question I had is
kind of piggybacking off

01:11:52.660 --> 01:11:55.940
of the previous question.

01:11:55.940 --> 01:11:58.550
And this is coming also
from me being an artist

01:11:58.550 --> 01:12:02.850
and having to think very
deeply about this, so.

01:12:02.850 --> 01:12:07.460
Do you think the native
art, native people in media,

01:12:07.460 --> 01:12:09.570
do you think their
work is inherently

01:12:09.570 --> 01:12:13.140
political, or radical?

01:12:13.140 --> 01:12:15.900
And also, how do
you deal with that

01:12:15.900 --> 01:12:18.970
with like looking at
your own positionalities

01:12:18.970 --> 01:12:20.550
and where you come from?

01:12:20.550 --> 01:12:25.720
And how do you sort of grapple
with being complicit or being

01:12:25.720 --> 01:12:27.900
or engaging in activism?

01:12:27.900 --> 01:12:28.610
-Hell, yeah.

01:12:28.610 --> 01:12:29.630
Yeah.

01:12:29.630 --> 01:12:30.460
-That's my student.

01:12:33.880 --> 01:12:37.500
-Again, man, you're
supposed to be dead.

01:12:37.500 --> 01:12:40.510
Everything you do
as a native person

01:12:40.510 --> 01:12:42.990
is either ironic,
or revolutionary,

01:12:42.990 --> 01:12:45.830
because nobody expects
you to even be there.

01:12:45.830 --> 01:12:47.550
So hell, yeah.

01:12:47.550 --> 01:12:50.880
Yeah You're doing something
big, just by existing, just

01:12:50.880 --> 01:12:53.730
by going out and doing work.

01:12:53.730 --> 01:12:56.510
So.

01:12:56.510 --> 01:13:00.790
-I think even just
living in our villages

01:13:00.790 --> 01:13:04.370
up in Alaska, where we've
lived our subsistence hunting

01:13:04.370 --> 01:13:07.790
and fishing lifestyles
since the beginning of time.

01:13:07.790 --> 01:13:10.930
And the fact that
that is something

01:13:10.930 --> 01:13:15.170
that we've had to
continue to battle

01:13:15.170 --> 01:13:21.640
and continue to work
against pipelines,

01:13:21.640 --> 01:13:26.710
and do what we can for
environmental justice,

01:13:26.710 --> 01:13:30.490
or social justice,
economic justice.

01:13:30.490 --> 01:13:36.460
All these aspects
are just us being us.

01:13:36.460 --> 01:13:43.810
And it's a strange thing
to think that, oh, well,

01:13:43.810 --> 01:13:45.260
you don't understand.

01:13:45.260 --> 01:13:49.000
If you take away our
subsistence hunting and fishing,

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:53.550
and it's $12 a gallon
for milk, that village

01:13:53.550 --> 01:13:55.650
is going to have to dismantle.

01:13:55.650 --> 01:14:01.260
They're going to leave their
lands and not live that way.

01:14:01.260 --> 01:14:08.040
And out of that dismantling,
a genocide has occurred.

01:14:08.040 --> 01:14:14.380
So just the fact of wanting to
maintain the traditions in life

01:14:14.380 --> 01:14:24.230
that we live and exist in is
in itself its own, as you said,

01:14:24.230 --> 01:14:31.400
it's a protest, or it's
irony or politicism

01:14:31.400 --> 01:14:35.120
just by being who you are.

01:14:35.120 --> 01:14:38.470
-[NON-ENGLISH] Hello, welcome.

01:14:38.470 --> 01:14:39.630
My name is Leah.

01:14:39.630 --> 01:14:41.740
I'm from the Narragansett
nation of Rhode Island,

01:14:41.740 --> 01:14:43.310
just further south of here.

01:14:43.310 --> 01:14:44.690
Welcome to the East Coast.

01:14:44.690 --> 01:14:47.660
And being an East Coast person,
the question I have for you

01:14:47.660 --> 01:14:52.670
as media professionals
is every year,

01:14:52.670 --> 01:14:56.060
Thanksgiving time, we deal
with a Thanksgiving story.

01:14:56.060 --> 01:14:59.840
My partner being Wampanoag,
me being an East Coast person.

01:14:59.840 --> 01:15:03.950
That is our time where
productions come out

01:15:03.950 --> 01:15:05.940
such as Saints and Strangers.

01:15:05.940 --> 01:15:07.820
And quite a few
people in the room

01:15:07.820 --> 01:15:11.400
are familiar with the disaster
of which that film was,

01:15:11.400 --> 01:15:15.720
in which native people,
unfortunately, I

01:15:15.720 --> 01:15:21.110
believe they were
misled into this film

01:15:21.110 --> 01:15:26.620
and portraying Wampanoag people
and people of the East Coast

01:15:26.620 --> 01:15:29.890
in the slate that was
not accurate whatsoever.

01:15:29.890 --> 01:15:35.660
And I was wondering how
you feel about the ethics

01:15:35.660 --> 01:15:38.980
of native people, or what the
ethics are of native people

01:15:38.980 --> 01:15:42.220
portraying other native
people from which they are not

01:15:42.220 --> 01:15:44.530
familiar with?

01:15:44.530 --> 01:15:47.890
And I know Irene has done
some great work in portraying

01:15:47.890 --> 01:15:49.770
many different people.

01:15:49.770 --> 01:15:54.280
And what are those ethics
that you follow as an actor?

01:15:54.280 --> 01:15:57.920
And what would you suggest
for other people who are

01:15:57.920 --> 01:16:01.310
going into that acting world?

01:16:01.310 --> 01:16:06.340
-I've been on many projects
where, literally, it was just

01:16:06.340 --> 01:16:10.600
assumed that I speak that
particular language, or subset

01:16:10.600 --> 01:16:18.160
of songs, or know how to wear
a certain piece of regalia,

01:16:18.160 --> 01:16:20.780
clothing.

01:16:20.780 --> 01:16:28.660
And it's been a long while
from the very first film

01:16:28.660 --> 01:16:34.950
that I worked on, when realizing
like I am not just an actor,

01:16:34.950 --> 01:16:37.670
I am an ambassador
and a teacher,

01:16:37.670 --> 01:16:40.500
and I have a whole lot of
other things on my shoulders

01:16:40.500 --> 01:16:44.650
than just going out and
portraying this woman that I

01:16:44.650 --> 01:16:46.460
did all my history research on.

01:16:46.460 --> 01:16:51.150
And I did all the things that
I would do from a point of view

01:16:51.150 --> 01:16:54.140
approaching any character.

01:16:54.140 --> 01:16:59.670
But it's gotten
better in the realms

01:16:59.670 --> 01:17:05.680
of where there have been more
extensive casting directors who

01:17:05.680 --> 01:17:09.500
do more extensive
work in finding people

01:17:09.500 --> 01:17:12.180
from those traditions,
those tribes.

01:17:12.180 --> 01:17:16.850
But the thing that
I hold on to is

01:17:16.850 --> 01:17:20.670
that I come from a
cultural perspective

01:17:20.670 --> 01:17:23.370
of belonging to a tribe.

01:17:23.370 --> 01:17:27.910
Strangely enough, I've never
spoken my own language, yet.

01:17:27.910 --> 01:17:38.000
But so I have those abilities
to know what to ask for,

01:17:38.000 --> 01:17:44.530
and what to push
for, and who to ask,

01:17:44.530 --> 01:17:46.480
and who should be presented.

01:17:46.480 --> 01:17:49.849
And literally, on one
film, out of speaking

01:17:49.849 --> 01:17:51.390
with the producers
and the directors,

01:17:51.390 --> 01:17:57.340
they went and hired someone
to represent the tribe

01:17:57.340 --> 01:18:02.530
that we were representing to
be there as a cultural advisor.

01:18:02.530 --> 01:18:07.200
And so that has that happens
more and more often, but still

01:18:07.200 --> 01:18:09.390
not enough.

01:18:09.390 --> 01:18:14.780
And to find that kind
of realm between someone

01:18:14.780 --> 01:18:22.170
who has the financial power
to make this million dollar

01:18:22.170 --> 01:18:26.190
film be sold in some
form of distribution,

01:18:26.190 --> 01:18:30.360
yet at the same time
represents native people.

01:18:30.360 --> 01:18:32.850
Yet, you hear people say,
oh, well we looked for people

01:18:32.850 --> 01:18:34.600
but we couldn't find
them, because there's

01:18:34.600 --> 01:18:35.400
nobody out there.

01:18:35.400 --> 01:18:37.160
And you go, what?

01:18:37.160 --> 01:18:40.180
So it's been a long struggle.

01:18:40.180 --> 01:18:41.330
It is a long struggle.

01:18:41.330 --> 01:18:43.510
It will continue to be that way.

01:18:43.510 --> 01:18:51.350
We just have to create
more of a group of people

01:18:51.350 --> 01:18:54.120
from every community,
if that's the case, who

01:18:54.120 --> 01:18:56.420
are both behind the camera,
in front of the camera.

01:18:56.420 --> 01:18:58.860
That is something that our
production company is working

01:18:58.860 --> 01:19:04.061
to do, and others are working
toward doing, is to create

01:19:04.061 --> 01:19:07.410
a workforce of us
in our communities

01:19:07.410 --> 01:19:12.060
that understand and
know this business.

