01:21:08.130 --> 01:21:10.210
Just a couple
reflections to conclude.

01:21:10.210 --> 01:21:13.600
The diversity, we
kept on coming back

01:21:13.600 --> 01:21:16.690
to stories and storytelling,
and the diversity of stories

01:21:16.690 --> 01:21:20.260
that we've heard in, the
forms in which they were told.

01:21:20.260 --> 01:21:25.190
Just this last panel, stories
being told through data.

01:21:25.190 --> 01:21:27.220
Adrienne's data.

01:21:27.220 --> 01:21:31.460
Irene Bedard's data,
quantitative visual data.

01:21:31.460 --> 01:21:35.170
Richard Guest's data on how
often people won or lost

01:21:35.170 --> 01:21:36.810
in front of the Supreme Court.

01:21:36.810 --> 01:21:41.600
Stories told with statistics,
a tool, of native politics.

01:21:41.600 --> 01:21:44.226
Stories through
visual representation.

01:21:44.226 --> 01:21:49.200
Matika Wilbur, obviously, but
also Kristiana Kahakauwila's

01:21:49.200 --> 01:21:52.570
inversion or
resplicing, if you will,

01:21:52.570 --> 01:21:57.340
of the map of the Pacific,
of Oceana, I'm sorry.

01:21:57.340 --> 01:22:00.530
Stories told through
political battle tales

01:22:00.530 --> 01:22:05.630
won and lost, sometimes
funny, sometimes not funny.

01:22:05.630 --> 01:22:09.080
Stories through violence retold,
whether domestic violence,

01:22:09.080 --> 01:22:13.950
sexual violence, symbolic
violence, military violence.

01:22:13.950 --> 01:22:18.590
Stories through song, not just
Frank Wong's beautiful hip hop,

01:22:18.590 --> 01:22:20.720
but also Jonathan
Perry this morning.

01:22:20.720 --> 01:22:22.360
Thank you, again.

01:22:22.360 --> 01:22:24.330
Story through comedy.

01:22:24.330 --> 01:22:27.280
Story through tragedy.

01:22:27.280 --> 01:22:30.330
As I listened to
the third panel,

01:22:30.330 --> 01:22:34.300
with Kristiana Kahakauwila
repieced together the Pacific,

01:22:34.300 --> 01:22:39.390
making whole again Oceana,
and as I wiped away two tears,

01:22:39.390 --> 01:22:42.360
I think there were
two, listening

01:22:42.360 --> 01:22:45.490
to Frank Wong and
his song, and as I

01:22:45.490 --> 01:22:48.610
listen to Irene Bedard
talk about being

01:22:48.610 --> 01:22:52.130
whole on our feet, where the
left wing and the right wing

01:22:52.130 --> 01:22:54.820
are part of the same animal.

01:22:54.820 --> 01:22:58.260
As I listened to
these storytellers,

01:22:58.260 --> 01:23:01.650
I realize that together,
everybody here today, we

01:23:01.650 --> 01:23:05.690
had, even if partially, been
made whole today ourselves.

01:23:05.690 --> 01:23:09.170
Maybe some of us had
even been healed.

01:23:09.170 --> 01:23:12.570
And for that I want to
thank the person who really

01:23:12.570 --> 01:23:15.050
is most responsible for
putting this all together,

01:23:15.050 --> 01:23:18.400
because she signed on to the
idea about a year and a half

01:23:18.400 --> 01:23:18.900
ago, now.

01:23:18.900 --> 01:23:20.860
A lot of planning goes
into this conference.

01:23:20.860 --> 01:23:25.240
And that's Dean Liz Cohen,
our fearless leader.

01:23:25.240 --> 01:23:27.550
And as of last
night, with the gift

01:23:27.550 --> 01:23:31.760
from Matika Wilbur, Chief Cohen.

01:23:31.760 --> 01:23:34.590
And I say that because
that was because that

01:23:34.590 --> 01:23:36.010
was Matika's thing.

01:23:36.010 --> 01:23:39.280
Becky Wasserman, director of
academic ventures at Radcliffe.

01:23:39.280 --> 01:23:42.630
Paul Beran, this
amazing Radcliffe staff,

01:23:42.630 --> 01:23:44.830
that runs these
conferences like a machine

01:23:44.830 --> 01:23:47.050
that you can set your watch to.

01:23:47.050 --> 01:23:49.280
Right?

01:23:49.280 --> 01:23:54.510
HUNAP and the amazing work
